5:000014497	6:gr-14497	3:Neverwhere (London Below, #1)	4:book review	60:Neverwhere (London Below, #1)	61:Neil Gaiman	62:2003	64:William Morrow Paperbacks	68:read	69:2011-06-07	63:9780060557812	67:5/5	70:Great as always. I love books that leave you with a smile.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14497
5:000014498	6:gr-14498	3:Neil Gaiman's Neverwhere	4:book review	60:Neil Gaiman's Neverwhere	61:Mike Carey	62:2007	64:Vertigo	68:read	69:2011-01-01	63:9781401210076	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14498
5:014546626	6:gr-14546626	3:Total Recall: My Unbelievably True Life Story	4:book review	60:Total Recall: My Unbelievably True Life Story	61:Arnold Schwarzenegger	62:2012	64:Simon & Schuster	68:read	69:2014-03-30	63:9781451662436	67:3/5	70:It's been said before, but the first half of this book is really the only part worth reading. If it had ended there another star would be forthcoming. I suppose it's possible that some folks might enjoy all the politics of part two, but that's not what I was looking for when it comes to Arnold's story.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14546626
5:000147504	6:gr-147504	3:Nova Command (Star Trek: The Next Generation - Starfleet Academy, #9)	4:book review	60:Nova Command (Star Trek: The Next Generation - Starfleet Academy, #9)	61:Brad Strickland	62:1995	64:Pocket Books	68:read	69:2017-02-09	63:9780671510091	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/147504
5:000147636	6:gr-147636	3:The Holy Bible: King James Version	4:book review	60:The Holy Bible: King James Version	61:Anonymous	62:2000	64:Thomas Nelson	68:read	69:1987-01-01	63:9780840726841	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/147636
5:000148191	6:gr-148191	3:Rimbaud: Poems	4:book review	60:Rimbaud: Poems	61:Arthur Rimbaud	62:1994	64:Everyman's Library	68:read	69:2014-01-01	63:9780679433217	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/148191
5:000014891	6:gr-14891	3:A Tree Grows in Brooklyn	4:book review	60:A Tree Grows in Brooklyn	61:Betty  Smith	62:2006	64:HarperCollins Publishers	68:read	69:2000-01-01	63:9780061120077	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14891
5:014919107	6:gr-14919107	3:Saints and Lovers	4:book review	60:Saints and Lovers	61:Lorianne Karney	62:2005	64:PublishAmerica	68:read	69:2017-04-12	63:9781413749687	67:4/5	70:Lorianne Karney has excellent control of her craft. The writing in Saints and Lovers evokes the essence of a journal or even a wandering train-of-thought. You quickly come to realize that despite this style, the story is far from the natural rambling of free-writing. Karney has shaped the story in the guise of a confessional, so personal that at times it crosses into vulgar; yet, underneath this facade beats a singular story being revealed moment-by-moment.\n\nThis is not an easy read. It is not a summer read or a beach read or even a sleepy evening read. This book takes patience and care and the occasional back-tracking to re-read the last couple paragraphs when your mind wanders. A wandering mind is tough to avoid, too, because it is essentially what Karney is creating for us on the page.\n\nWhile elements of the story are viscerally real, so much of the common stage-setting description has been left out in ways I suspect were intentional. Without an anchor to moor us, the characters flitting in and out of dialogue and scene, memory and action, all seem a bit like will-o-the-wisps. Everything is painted in the dreamy half-light, half mist of memory, even the main character herself.\n\nWhat the book is about is debatable. By the end of the story it's not entirely clear that there was a singular vision for the plot, per se. There can be no doubt that there has been a change in the main character, however. This is what I see as the essential element to Saints and Lovers. The mind for all its daydreams and wanderings, memory, regret, pain and confusion; is capable of great change.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/14919107
