5:000015575	6:gr-15575	3:The Sword of Shannara (The Original Shannara Trilogy, #1)	4:book review	60:The Sword of Shannara (The Original Shannara Trilogy, #1)	61:Terry Brooks	62:1999	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2016-03-05	63:9781857231519	67:1/5	70:Awful writing. Just awful.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15575
5:156155983	6:gr-156155983	3:The Intelligence Illusion: a practical guide to the business risks of Generative AI	4:book review	60:The Intelligence Illusion: a practical guide to the business risks of Generative AI	61:Baldur Bjarnason	62:2023	64:Baldur Bjarnason	68:read	69:2023-06-01	67:5/5	70:This highly researched book delivers on the promise in a clear, organized way. What is generative AI and how might it affect your business? What are the pitfalls? Where are the charlatans? Where might be safe to dip in a toe? What are the risks and what are the potential rewards?\n\nBaldur does a fabulous job offering a critical take at the AI market. It's not so much of a take-down of the industry; he's far too balanced in his analysis for that. It does show how incredibly shaky the ground is and he offers great advice to those considering investment.\n\nIf you are a business leader or have input on the decision-making for your business then do yourself the favor of reading this book. I swear a quarter of the book is references and it reads very quickly.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/156155983
5:000015645	6:gr-15645	3:Inferno	4:book review	60:Inferno	61:Dante Alighieri	62:2003	64:Modern Library	68:read	63:9780812970067	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15645
5:015701981	6:gr-15701981	3:Critical Failures	4:book review	60:Critical Failures	61:Robert Bevan	62:2012	64:DeadPixel Publications	68:read	69:2018-01-01	67:2/5	70:I listened to the audiobook. I don't recommend that. I think there's a lot of things about this book that could have been better enjoyed without the style the narrator used in the Audible recording. I think there are a lot of things that wouldn't be fixed even by reading it in print.\n\nThe story is generic litRPG fare with an overabundance of farting, vomiting, and homophobia.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15701981
5:015704459	6:gr-15704459	3:Firefight (The Reckoners, #2)	4:book review	60:Firefight (The Reckoners, #2)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2015	64:Delacorte Press	68:read	69:2019-12-31	63:9780385743587	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15704459
5:015704486	6:gr-15704486	3:Calamity (Reckoners, #3)	4:book review	60:Calamity (Reckoners, #3)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2016	64:Delacorte Press	68:read	69:2019-12-31	63:9780385743600	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15704486
5:015713880	6:gr-15713880	3:Throne of Glass (Throne of Glass, #1)	4:book review	60:Throne of Glass (Throne of Glass, #1)	61:Sarah J. Maas	62:2012	64:Bloomsbury Children's	68:read	69:2018-12-16	67:1/5	70:DNF	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15713880
5:000157313	6:gr-157313	3:Squee	4:book review	60:Squee	61:Jhonen Vásquez	62:1998	64:SLG Publishing	68:read	69:2004-01-01	63:9780943151243	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/157313
5:015751758	6:gr-15751758	3:Dragon Badge	4:book review	60:Dragon Badge	61:Scott Moon	62:2012	64:Scott Moon	68:read	69:2013-09-02	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15751758
5:015797396	6:gr-15797396	3:Enon	4:book review	60:Enon	61:Paul Harding	62:2013	64:Random House	68:read	69:2017-01-15	63:9781400069439	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15797396
5:000157993	6:gr-157993	3:The Little Prince	4:book review	60:The Little Prince	61:Antoine de Saint-Exupéry	62:2000	64:Harcourt, Inc.	68:read	69:2004-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/157993
5:015803037	6:gr-15803037	3:Red Sparrow (Red Sparrow Trilogy, #1)	4:book review	60:Red Sparrow (Red Sparrow Trilogy, #1)	61:Jason  Matthews	62:2013	64:Scribner	68:read	69:2021-10-26	63:9781476706122	67:3/5	70:As far as spy stories go this lands somewhere between the Le Carre and the Ludlum. What worked? The SVR detail and cast of characters, especially those who avoided the sinister baddie vibe (aka, not Putin). What didn't work? The random choice to have a cookbook sprinkled throughout. It felt forced and broke the flow of the story in a negative way.\n\nThere's a bit too much coincidence in ways that I didn't buy. Nodding at them and saying, "It's like a Bond movie," didn't somehow magically make it okay.\n\nI'd like to try the next book in the story, but I think I'm gonna be a bit more critical going in.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15803037
5:015805962	6:gr-15805962	3:Hymnal for Dirty Girls	4:book review	60:Hymnal for Dirty Girls	61:Rebekah Matthews	62:2012	64:Big Rodent Books	68:read	69:2012-11-06	63:9780984487899	66:firstreads	67:2/5	70:I had to take a few days to think about how I should review this book. I received it in a Goodreads Giveaway, which I entered based almost entirely on the cover design and title. I knew nothing of the subject matter or format and that would have greatly affected my desire to pick it up in the first place.\n\nNext, I should be clear that my rating is, and must be, true to my own experience in reading the book. It does not necessarily depict the independent value or quality of the writing, the impact of the themes or subjects, or any other fancy writing concepts. On Goodreads, two stars means, "It was ok," and that is exactly how I felt after reading it. I suspect that those who pick this book up based on its content with an honest desire and interest in it will find the book much more enjoyable.\n\nThe format is also very hard to critique. This is a collection of extremely short stories. Some are no more than a single scene. It felt, at times, like the author was sharing a bunch of writing experiments with us. I can't very well critique them on lack of character development or anything like that because that's not the form of writing we're dealing with. For what they are, they are very well written. In a few stories the use of the second person perspective is a bit annoying and feels like the type of gimmick I'd expect from a college-level writing class. \n\nThere are a few moments of clear inspired writing in here, which is commendable. My overall impression was that of a small art exhibit in a big city, which spends more effort on being different and niche than on the craft itself.\n\nThe jacket notes mention that Ms. Matthews is currently writing a novel. I'd be interested in reading that to see how she handles the larger work and the many aspects of writing that come with it.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15805962
5:015808302	6:gr-15808302	3:Zeus Grants Stupid Wishes: A No-Bullshit Guide to World Mythology	4:book review	60:Zeus Grants Stupid Wishes: A No-Bullshit Guide to World Mythology	61:Cory O'Brien	62:2013	64:TarcherPerigee	68:read	69:2014-01-01	63:9780399160400	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15808302
5:015808380	6:gr-15808380	3:Between (The Between, #1)	4:book review	60:Between (The Between, #1)	61:Kerry Schafer	62:2013	64:Ace	68:read	69:2013-04-07	63:9780425261149	66:firstreads	67:2/5	70:This free "First Reads" book started off better than I expected. The author seemed to draw a lot of style from romance novels, though this doesn't ever go down the path of actual romance. I think the parts that dragged this book down the most were the failure to really set the scene and a lack of cohesion to the main character's, well, character. She was a strange mix of personality types that seemed to jump drastically. The medical knowledge seemed less appropriate for a doctor and more like a person who has had a lot of medical problems.\n\nDespite confusions as to waking, sleeping, and in-between modes (when she's already in a dream and someone knocks her out, where does that put us?) the overall concept is interesting and fun. I liked lots of large chunks of it, but it just couldn't pull itself up passed "ok" territory.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/15808380
