5:002020768	6:gr-2020768	3:I Am America (And So Can You!)	4:book review	60:I Am America (And So Can You!)	61:Stephen Colbert	62:2007	64:Grand Central Publishing	68:read	69:2014-01-01	63:9781600240362	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2020768
5:020211434	6:gr-20211434	3:The Essential Rumi	4:book review	60:The Essential Rumi	61:Rumi	62:2010	64:HarperCollins e-books	68:read	69:2005-01-01	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20211434
5:000020249	6:gr-20249	3:Hunters of Dune (Dune, #7)	4:book review	60:Hunters of Dune (Dune, #7)	61:Brian Herbert	62:2006	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2019-10-03	63:9780765312921	67:2/5	70:These last two Dune books are so hard to rate. In the one hand I'm thrilled to get the end of the saga, but the quality of the writing is a pale shadow of what Frank Herbert gave us. Brian Herbert and Kevin J. Anderson are not great at this. They were the ones that got ahold of the notes and made it happen, though, and for that I'm grateful. \n\nChapterhouse ends in a mighty cliffhanger and these books do resolve that, but they do it sloppily. This story is by turns boringly drawn out, painfully on-the-nose, and filled with exposition. In this way, Hunters is like a lot of modern science fiction, more concerned with the things thought up than the story being told.\n\nThere are some revelations that strike at irregular intervals, like the footsteps of a Fremen Frank Herbert across the otherwise barren landscape of these pages. Or perhaps his notes are like the waters of Dune, rare and treasured, and just plentiful enough for us to survive.\n\nIf you are not a giant fan of Dune, do not bother with these books. If your interest waned in books 5 and 6, don't continue on. If you are just dying to know the end so you can close that door in your mind, maybe you should read the Wikipedia page instead. If you do read it, expect a story from a lesser storyteller, an echo of the original like a Ghola unawakened.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20249
5:020257417	6:gr-20257417	3:The Sword of Elseerian (The Chronicles of Lumineia: The White Mage Saga, #2)	4:book review	60:The Sword of Elseerian (The Chronicles of Lumineia: The White Mage Saga, #2)	61:Ben Hale	62:2013	64:Amazon Digital Services, Inc.	68:read	69:2016-07-03	67:1/5	70:This was an unfortunate turn. Book one of the series may have been derivative, but it was well written and fun. Book two was a hodge-podge of exposition and unnatural characterization.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/20257417
5:000202650	6:gr-202650	3:The Kitáb-i-Íqán: The Book of Certitude	4:book review	60:The Kitáb-i-Íqán: The Book of Certitude	61:Bahá'u'lláh	62:2003	64:Baha'i Publishing	68:read	69:2011-08-30	63:9781931847087	67:4/5	70:Some really powerful and moving stuff here. Great food for thought and the soul.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/202650
