5:023437156	6:gr-23437156	3:Six of Crows (Six of Crows, #1)	4:book review	60:Six of Crows (Six of Crows, #1)	61:Leigh Bardugo	62:2015	64:Henry Holt & Company	68:read	69:2016-11-04	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23437156
5:000023454	6:gr-23454	3:Dragons of Winter Night (Dragonlance: Chronicles, #2)	4:book review	60:Dragons of Winter Night (Dragonlance: Chronicles, #2)	61:Margaret Weis	62:2007	64:Devil's Due Publishing	68:read	69:1995-01-01	63:9781932796780	67:4/5	70:Re-reading this with my son was wonderful. There's so much more going on than in the first book, and he was highly invested all along the way. The reappearance of a beloved character thought lost in book one was a celebration, and the tragic ending was very emotional. He really loved the colors of the dragons revealing a bit more about them and their relationships, and he's eager to see what happens next in Spring.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23454
5:023464655	6:gr-23464655	3:Sunset (Nightlord, #1)	4:book review	60:Sunset (Nightlord, #1)	61:Garon Whited	62:2014	68:read	69:2023-08-27	67:1/5	70:Incoherent characterization of the protagonist is the ultimate failing, but this also managed to be a Mary Sue as well. Others have reviewed this more thoroughly already so I'll be quick: the morals of the main character make no sense. The nonchalance of becoming a vampire and learning magic was a missed opportunity to say something interesting. Being automatically good at everything is boring. Inconsistent power levels make it frustrating to follow.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23464655
5:023485372	6:gr-23485372	3:The Master Magician (The Paper Magician, #3)	4:book review	60:The Master Magician (The Paper Magician, #3)	61:Charlie N. Holmberg	62:2015	64:47North	68:read	69:2017-06-11	63:1477878696	67:5/5	70:Really solid ending to the trilogy.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23485372
5:000234894	6:gr-234894	3:The Hero's Adventure: Power of Myth 1	4:book review	60:The Hero's Adventure: Power of Myth 1	61:Joseph Campbell	62:1992	64:Highbridge Audio	68:read	69:2018-07-01	63:9780942110937	67:5/5	70:This first volume is almost a summary of the Hero With 1000 Faces. Worth a listen.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/234894
5:000234895	6:gr-234895	3:The First Storytellers: Power of Myth 3	4:book review	60:The First Storytellers: Power of Myth 3	61:Joseph Campbell	62:1992	64:HighBridge Audio	68:read	69:2018-07-01	63:9780942110951	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/234895
5:023533039	6:gr-23533039	3:Ancillary Mercy (Imperial Radch, #3)	4:book review	60:Ancillary Mercy (Imperial Radch, #3)	61:Ann Leckie	62:2015	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2020-08-27	63:9780356502427	67:5/5	70:This series was really great. The point of views and gender wordplay seem like gimicks at the start, but they develop through significant phases to become core parts of the theme. By the end there were several characters whose gender became irrelevant to me in the exact way that it seemed to the Radachaii. Those differences in perspective formed a brilliant lens through which to understand the Preseger, the fully "other" alien race that held humanity in check.\n\nThe ending is intensely satisfying, but even were it otherwise the character growth demonstrated by the full cast was impressive as hell.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23533039
5:023546843	6:gr-23546843	3:Ms. Marvel, Vol. 3: Crushed	4:book review	60:Ms. Marvel, Vol. 3: Crushed	61:G. Willow Wilson	62:2015	64:Marvel Comics	68:read	69:2021-10-17	63:9780785192275	67:4/5	70:The new Ms. Marvel is a joy. Still plenty of innocence, snark, and interesting family drama. Volume 3 was great development for her character and hints at more revelations to come. I liked it more than Volume 2.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23546843
5:023547364	6:gr-23547364	3:Knight's Shadow (Greatcoats, #2)	4:book review	60:Knight's Shadow (Greatcoats, #2)	61:Sebastien de Castell	62:2015	64:Jo Fletcher Books	68:read	69:2019-02-05	63:9781782066774	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/23547364
5:000235964	6:gr-235964	3:Rock and Roll Mystery (Choose Your Own Adventure, #69)	4:book review	60:Rock and Roll Mystery (Choose Your Own Adventure, #69)	61:Jim Wallace	62:1987	64:Bantam Books	68:read	69:2018-11-15	63:9780553266535	67:1/5	70:This book barely made any sense. The endings were all let downs that undermined the value of our choices throughout. So far, one of the worst CYOAs I've read.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/235964
5:000236093	6:gr-236093	3:The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (Oz, #1)	4:book review	60:The Wonderful Wizard of Oz (Oz, #1)	61:L. Frank Baum	62:1995	64:Penguin	68:read	69:2012-03-04	63:9780140621679	67:3/5	70:I bought this book with the intention of building up a little library of children's stories for my kids. Along with The Wonderful Wizard of Oz, I also purchased The Monkey With a Notion (not listed on Goodreads), and a first edition [b:Where the Wild Things Are|19543|Where the Wild Things Are|Maurice Sendak|http://photo.goodreads.com/books/1327878051s/19543.jpg|3020535]. I'd like to gather up all the classic fairy tales used in Disney movies so (s)he has a nice foundation.\n\nAs far as The Wizard of Oz is concerned, I found it very interesting that Mr. Baum decided to create such a rich fantasy story with no apparent lesson at all. He addresses this in the introduction to the book as being a conscious decision. He explains, the fairy tales of the past were riddled with horror and consequence in order to impart some moral lesson. However, in this "modern" age, moral education is so pervasive, he felt these tactics were unnecessary, and instead sought to provide a purely entertaining story. I would love to share his views on modern education, but I very much doubt that anyone could honestly claim our age imparts such strong moral convictions anymore.\n\nThe Wonderful Wizard of Oz brought me the most enjoyment in finding where it diverged from the film, for instance, when the Wicked Witch of the West is defeated about halfway through the book. Such interesting changes from the familiar are entertaining, but I wonder how they will appeal to a young child. Perhaps I expect too much from it, though. In a child's world, when heroes encounter a problem, they solve that one and move on. There need be no more complexity than that. They won't care to go searching for a deeper meaning in the Scarecrow or Lion. Perhaps it is enough after all.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/236093
