5:025444441	6:gr-25444441	3:The Assassins of Altis (The Pillars of Reality, #3)	4:book review	60:The Assassins of Altis (The Pillars of Reality, #3)	61:Jack Campbell	62:2015	64:Audible Studios on Brilliance Audio	68:read	69:2017-06-27	63:9781491540244	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25444441
5:025451852	6:gr-25451852	3:Dawn of Wonder (The Wakening, #1)	4:book review	60:Dawn of Wonder (The Wakening, #1)	61:Jonathan Renshaw	62:2015	64:Jonathan Renshaw	68:read	69:2017-02-25	67:2/5	70:This is a tough book to review. There were so many things going right, but the pacing and structure of the story made it drag for me. Did the book need to be this long? Probably not. I think the segmentation of plots into discrete parts was the ultimate downfall. Had some of these threads interwoven and worked together it would have seemed less episodic, and I would have felt like there was a cohesive story. As it was, I was bored by the end of the book and just waiting for it to wrap up.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25451852
5:000002547	6:gr-2547	3:The Prophet	4:book review	60:The Prophet	61:Kahlil Gibran	62:2003	64:Rupa & Co	68:read	69:2010-01-01	63:9780001000391	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2547
5:025489134	6:gr-25489134	3:The Bear and the Nightingale (The Winternight Trilogy, #1)	4:book review	60:The Bear and the Nightingale (The Winternight Trilogy, #1)	61:Katherine Arden	62:2017	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2017-01-01	63:9781101885932	67:1/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25489134
5:025499718	6:gr-25499718	3:Children of Time (Children of Time, #1)	4:book review	60:Children of Time (Children of Time, #1)	61:Adrian Tchaikovsky	62:2015	64:PanMacmillan	68:read	69:2018-04-27	63:9781447273288	67:4/5	70:I wish I'd known that spiders feature prominently in this story. I would have avoided it on that alone and saved myself so much squeamishness.\n\nOther than the spider thing the story is quite good and not obvious or predictable.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25499718
5:025587066	6:gr-25587066	3:The Wedding & Disaster of Felona Mabel	4:book review	60:The Wedding & Disaster of Felona Mabel	61:Kenn Bivins	62:2015	64:Invisible Ennk Press	68:read	69:2015-10-21	63:9780985370725	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25587066
5:025618459	6:gr-25618459	3:The Black Star of Kingston (Tales of Old Natalia #1)	4:book review	60:The Black Star of Kingston (Tales of Old Natalia #1)	61:S.D.   Smith	62:2015	64:Story Warren Books	68:read	69:2019-09-29	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25618459
5:025655835	6:gr-25655835	3:Get Out of Denver (Denver Burning Book 1)	4:book review	60:Get Out of Denver (Denver Burning Book 1)	61:Algor X. Dennison	62:2015	68:read	67:1/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25655835
5:025656828	6:gr-25656828	3:Professional Integrity (The Riyria Chronicles, #2.6)	4:book review	60:Professional Integrity (The Riyria Chronicles, #2.6)	61:Michael J. Sullivan	62:2015	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2015-12-20	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25656828
5:025667918	6:gr-25667918	3:Binti (Binti, #1)	4:book review	60:Binti (Binti, #1)	61:Nnedi Okorafor	62:2015	64:Tor.com	68:read	69:2019-02-23	63:9780765384461	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25667918
5:000256683	6:gr-256683	3:City of Bones (The Mortal Instruments, #1)	4:book review	60:City of Bones (The Mortal Instruments, #1)	61:Cassandra Clare	62:2007	64:Margaret K. McElderry Books	68:read	69:2012-01-29	63:9781416914280	67:2/5	70:(I'm going to murder Goodreads for just deleting the huge, detailed review I just wrote. Let's see if I have the patience to do this again)\n\nCity of Bones, the first Mortal Instruments novel, is about as unremarkable as anything I've read in the past five years. The characters are flat, the plots are lifted from well known tropes (and implemented ungracefully), the descriptions are hammy and ill-timed, and the narrative voice will convince you that your author would rather be nerding-out watching anime than really writing a book.\n\nThe main character, Clary, is prototypically insecure as a regular mortal thrust into a magical world that's all new and shiny. The concept makes you roll your eyes, and it only gets worse from there. What surprises lay in store for our young heroine? Will there be a love triangle? Perhaps someone will betray her, or maybe someone will reveal that they aren't who they claimed to be? Yeah, you'll see it all coming a mile away, and you won't really care.\n\nThe main supporting male lead, Jace, is a fantastic example of an author falling in love with her character. If I read one more paragraph about how amazing and infinitely talented he was, despite being a tormented bad-boy who must be forgiven his caustic personality, I think I might have hurled.\n\nAll-in-all, City of Bones is formulaic, mediocre, and boring. It reads at a young-adult level, so perhaps that audience will be more taken in by it. For myself, I will not be continuing the series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/256683
5:000025673	6:gr-25673	3:City of God	4:book review	60:City of God	61:Augustine of Hippo	62:2003	64:Penguin Books Ltd	68:read	69:2006-01-01	63:9780140448948	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25673
5:025692556	6:gr-25692556	3:Two Necromancers, an Army of Golems, and a Demon Lord (The Unconventional Heroes #2)	4:book review	60:Two Necromancers, an Army of Golems, and a Demon Lord (The Unconventional Heroes #2)	61:L.G. Estrella	62:2015	64:Amazon Digital Services	68:read	69:2021-03-12	67:1/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25692556
5:002572997	6:gr-2572997	3:Night Shift (Jill Kismet, #1)	4:book review	60:Night Shift (Jill Kismet, #1)	61:Lilith Saintcrow	62:2008	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2022-01-14	63:9780316001786	67:4/5	70:Sometimes you need some butt-kicking urban fantasy to cleanse the palette. You could do much worse than Jill Kismet. There's just enough worldbuilding to get the sense of a larger picture, but you're never too far from a bloody fight to get bogged down.\n\nI'm reading through the Omnibus version of the series and ticking these off one-by-one. They're lovely little murdery bedtime stories.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2572997
