5:037415696	6:gr-37415696	3:Killer by Nature	4:book review	60:Killer by Nature	61:Jan Smith	62:2017	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2020-01-15	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37415696
5:000374301	6:gr-374301	3:Doctor Who: Sting of the Zygons	4:book review	60:Doctor Who: Sting of the Zygons	61:Stephen Cole	62:2007	64:Random House UK	68:read	69:2013-05-28	63:9781846072253	67:3/5	70:I heard a rumor that Zygons would be returning to the series in the 50th anniversary. So I picked up this story as a quick reintroduction. It wasn't too bad, though I again felt the author missed the real "voice" of The Doctor.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/374301
5:003754016	6:gr-3754016	3:Shadow's Edge (Night Angel, #2)	4:book review	60:Shadow's Edge (Night Angel, #2)	61:Brent Weeks	62:2008	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2009-03-24	63:9780316033657	67:3/5	70:This book seemed a lot more haphazard than the first. Lots of interesting things happening still, but I'm finding the breaks from character group to character group less interesting each time they happen. We'll see what the next one has in store.\n\nReread: This book isn't so haphazard as I felt last time, but the focus is much more widespread. A lot of interesting new developments kick in here, and it is a nice world-building book. I really only have one beef with the story, and that is Kylar not bothering to change his name when he goes into hiding. Seriously? The best assassin in the world can't figure out that when laying low, you might not want to go by the same name that everyone knows? Yeesh.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3754016
5:003754026	6:gr-3754026	3:Beyond the Shadows (Night Angel, #3)	4:book review	60:Beyond the Shadows (Night Angel, #3)	61:Brent Weeks	62:2008	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2013-02-19	63:9780316033664	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3754026
5:037570536	6:gr-37570536	3:The Oregon Trail: Danger at the Haunted Gate (The Oregon Trail, 2)	4:book review	60:The Oregon Trail: Danger at the Haunted Gate (The Oregon Trail, 2)	61:Jesse Wiley	62:2018	64:Clarion Books	68:read	69:2019-03-13	63:9781328549976	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37570536
5:037570539	6:gr-37570539	3:The Race to Chimney Rock (The Oregon Trail, #1)	4:book review	60:The Race to Chimney Rock (The Oregon Trail, #1)	61:Jesse Wiley	62:2018	64:Clarion Books	68:read	69:2019-03-03	63:9781328550002	67:3/5	70:This is far less deadly than the game you might remember, but it makes up for it with some nice settings, a dash of history, and a sense of adventure.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37570539
5:000003758	6:gr-3758	3:Casino Royale (James Bond, #1)	4:book review	60:Casino Royale (James Bond, #1)	61:Ian Fleming	62:2002	64:Penguin	68:read	69:2003-01-01	63:9780142002025	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3758
5:000375802	6:gr-375802	3:Ender’s Game (Ender's Saga, #1)	4:book review	60:Ender’s Game (Ender's Saga, #1)	61:Orson Scott Card	62:2004	64:Tor	68:read	69:1997-01-01	63:9780812550702	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/375802
5:000037586	6:gr-37586	3:The Lost Colony (Artemis Fowl, #5)	4:book review	60:The Lost Colony (Artemis Fowl, #5)	61:Eoin Colfer	62:2006	64:Miramax Books/Hyperion Books for Children	68:read	69:2012-12-09	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37586
5:037654736	6:gr-37654736	3:Stuff and Nonsense (Threadbare #1)	4:book review	60:Stuff and Nonsense (Threadbare #1)	61:Andrew Seiple	62:2017	68:read	69:2022-01-30	67:3/5	70:As I've stated before, the genre of litRPG is not my favorite, but there have been a few exceptions. I'm going to have to put Threadbare's series on that list. The twist-factor of having the main character be an animated teddy bear was enough to get me over the hump of the length leveling up notifications and other distracting tropes. The story even hinted that this RPG aspect is a relatively recent occurrence in the world, and possibly plot related. Tricks are nice, but ultimately what sets a story apart is the storytelling itself. Here I think Andrew Seiple did a very fine job. He "humanized" some non-human characters in creative ways and gave us fascinating points-of-view while subjecting these same characters to trials which would test their inner strengths. Whether that character was a teddy bear, an orc shaman, or a 20lb house cat, Seiple's prose did it justice.\n\nI will pick up the next in the series and I hope to see more of our precocious teddy in action.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37654736
5:003766428	6:gr-3766428	3:Double Share (Golden Age of the Solar Clipper, #4)	4:book review	60:Double Share (Golden Age of the Solar Clipper, #4)	61:Nathan Lowell	62:2008	64:Podiobooks	68:read	69:2014-09-14	67:1/5	70:Wow. The enjoyment I've been getting from this series derives almost entirely from the low-conflict, light-hearted nature of the books. Double Share takes that and throws it out the window. My first reaction was positive. This could be something new, something great. Then reality set in.\n\nRather than the Lois McKendrick, our protaganists' home in the Deep Dark for the past few books, we now move the setting to a new ship, the William Tinker. This ship is gross. It's filthy, smells, everyone is nasty to one another, and, oh yeah, the entire female crew is being constantly raped.\n\nI absolutely hate rape stories, whether in book, TV, or film. They make me want to throw up, and that's not how I enjoy spending my light-hearted reading time. Really, the only way to make it worse is to treat the rape as anything less than horrific. Guess what Nathan Lowell managed to do?\n\nI'm not going to really spoil anything here because this book can't get any more spoiled. In the end, after the dust has settled and things are "resolved", the new female captain (who has witnessed these atrocities happening for years) keeps one of the rapists aboard. The character even manages to explain away what he did by saying "he's a good boy that fell in with a bad crowd". How about we tell that to the women he raped time and time again over the course of YEARS while they had no means of escape except the emptiness of space? How about we go back to the part when we learn that he has murdered women that have tried to fight back or complain?\n\nThis book was digsusting. Much more so than the William Tinker.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3766428
5:000377510	6:gr-377510	3:A Pilgrim's Journey: The Autobiography of St. Ignatius of Loyola	4:book review	60:A Pilgrim's Journey: The Autobiography of St. Ignatius of Loyola	61:Ignatius of Loyola	62:2001	64:Beaufort Books	68:read	69:2009-01-01	63:9780898708103	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/377510
5:037794149	6:gr-37794149	3:A Memory Called Empire (Teixcalaan, #1)	4:book review	60:A Memory Called Empire (Teixcalaan, #1)	61:Arkady Martine	62:2019	64:Tor	68:read	69:2022-01-01	63:9781529001587	67:1/5	70:Boring as sin. The reader of the audiobook did it no justice. (Note: the reader did a wonderful job in Forging Hephaestus and its sequel, just not in this outting.)\n\nIt starts strong enough with a lot of world-building and some interesting tech that facilitates deep internal conversations. But then it gets bogged down in dialogue and exposition, drags onwards for hundreds of pages, and ultimately there's no payoff for your efforts. It has lots of potential and maybe future books will be better in the series that it sets up, but I won't be reading them.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37794149
5:000000378	6:gr-378	3:The Phantom Tollbooth	4:book review	60:The Phantom Tollbooth	61:Norton Juster	62:1996	64:Random House Bullseye Books	68:read	69:1993-01-01	63:9780394820378	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/378
5:037841552	6:gr-37841552	3:Learn Bash the Hard Way	4:book review	60:Learn Bash the Hard Way	61:Ian Miell	62:2018	64:Lean Publishing	68:read	69:2018-01-13	67:5/5	70:This book is fantastic. Follow the instructions and actually enter all the commands as they happen. Digging into seemingly simple questions really helped me grok everything. I think I'll give one more read to the section on traps, but otherwise I feel so much stronger in my BASH-FU.\n\nDo you work in the terminal? Do yourself a favor and read this.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37841552
5:037918381	6:gr-37918381	3:Arduino books: 5 Books in 1- Beginner's Guide+ Tips and Tricks+ Simple and Effective strategies+ Best practices & Advanced strategies	4:book review	60:Arduino books: 5 Books in 1- Beginner's Guide+ Tips and Tricks+ Simple and Effective strategies+ Best practices & Advanced strategies	61:Daniel Jones	62:2018	68:read	69:2018-02-03	67:2/5	70:There's some good information in these books but the method of presentation leaves a lot to be desired. There's much better getting-started guides that take you through the hardware and software more naturally. Once we reach the intermediate or advanced topics we should be able to shed the basic terminology interruptions. This series begins, bafflingly, with the Arduino language structure, covering data types and control statements, instead of focusing on the device itself. It isn't until book three that the "for loop" is addressed directly. This sort of nonsensical organization makes the books almost useless.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/37918381
5:000379464	6:gr-379464	3:Catholic for a Reason II: Scripture and the Mystery of the Mother of God	4:book review	60:Catholic for a Reason II: Scripture and the Mystery of the Mother of God	61:Leon J. Suprenant Jr.	62:2005	64:Emmaus Road Publishing	68:read	69:2012-07-28	63:9781931018234	66:firstreads	67:2/5	70:This book might be interesting to Protestants, our that very rare animal, the Catholic theology nerd.For me it was tedious and wordy. It was overly technical and needlessly referenced. \n\nThis book was about Mary, and answers to common misconceptions and criticisms of her in Catholic teaching. With a subject that could be so interesting and filled with such love, I was mortified to find instead the same annoying religious buzzwords and archaic speech that makes me roll my eyes at evangelicals being used to justify dogma legalistically.\n\nI was disappointed, and frankly, bored. Mary is far too interesting a person for this.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/379464
5:038093768	6:gr-38093768	3:The Man on the Mountaintop	4:book review	60:The Man on the Mountaintop	61:Susan Trott	62:2017	64:Audible	68:read	69:2020-02-01	67:3/5	70:There was a lot of little joys in this book. Sometimes it triggered an eyeroll as the little old holy man instantly solved someone's lifetime problem with a quirky sentence. In the spirit of the book I tried to keep a generous mind and let it lead me toward a simple thought, that every person is a holy person.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38093768
5:000038169	6:gr-38169	3:Alas, Babylon	4:book review	60:Alas, Babylon	61:Pat Frank	62:2005	64:Harper Perennial Modern Classics	68:read	69:2021-02-27	63:9780060741877	67:2/5	70:Alas, Babylon was well written and well narrated by Will Patton. There's quite a bit of tension in the beginning and the writing skillfully shows the beautiful horror of the unknown. It clenches at your chest at times.\n\nOn the other hand, knowing what I do of events at that time I couldn't fully immerse myself in the fear and worry. Everything was a bit silly when it had no right being that way. So it caught me off guard when history diverged from narrative. I had to take a moment and look at the book more closely to see the publication date and say, "ahha!"\n\nAction from that point on had a different vibe and not an altogether kind one. Elements I'd considered included for historical accuracy turned out to just be plain old racism, and in the face of what was happening it all seemed the more absurd. Characterization fell apart and the story spiraled for me. I lost interest toward the end.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38169
5:038203037	6:gr-38203037	3:Harry Clarke	4:book review	60:Harry Clarke	61:David Cale	62:2018	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2019-02-25	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38203037
5:038212615	6:gr-38212615	3:Sew You Want to be a Hero (Threadbare #2)	4:book review	60:Sew You Want to be a Hero (Threadbare #2)	61:Andrew Seiple	62:2018	68:read	69:2022-03-18	67:3/5	70:Teddy bear litrpg adventures continue in this second volume.. Not a lot of new ground being broken, but some fun characters and humor.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38212615
5:038322550	6:gr-38322550	3:The Last Emperox (The Interdependency, #3)	4:book review	60:The Last Emperox (The Interdependency, #3)	61:John Scalzi	62:2020	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2020-06-09	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38322550
5:000383444	6:gr-383444	3:Back to Basics: A Complete Guide to Traditional Skills	4:book review	60:Back to Basics: A Complete Guide to Traditional Skills	61:Abigail R. Gehring	62:2007	64:Skyhorse Publishing	68:read	69:2013-01-01	63:9781602391680	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/383444
5:000383514	6:gr-383514	3:Her Royal Spyness (Her Royal Spyness Mysteries, #1)	4:book review	60:Her Royal Spyness (Her Royal Spyness Mysteries, #1)	61:Rhys Bowen	62:2007	64:Berkley Publishing Group	68:read	69:2021-04-23	63:9780425215678	67:3/5	70:Lovely fun cozy mystery. I think the "spy" angle was overblown here, but perhaps we'll go more in that direction as the series progresses.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/383514
5:000003836	6:gr-3836	3:Don Quixote	4:book review	60:Don Quixote	61:Miguel de Cervantes Saavedra	62:2003	64:Penguin Books	68:read	69:1996-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3836
5:038362809	6:gr-38362809	3:Rosewater (The Wormwood Trilogy, #1)	4:book review	60:Rosewater (The Wormwood Trilogy, #1)	61:Tade Thompson	62:2018	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2023-07-14	63:9780316449052	67:2/5	70:DNF: I reached 91% complete in this book before I realized I just didn't care. The hypersexuality that would pop in routinely was so jarring and out of place it kept kicking me out of what should have otherwise been an interesting story. With that extra distance everything sort of felt bland. The further disconnected from normality things got, the more that blandness really felt strange. I don't think I'll continue in this series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38362809
5:000038447	6:gr-38447	3:The Handmaid’s Tale (The Handmaid's Tale, #1)	4:book review	60:The Handmaid’s Tale (The Handmaid's Tale, #1)	61:Margaret Atwood	62:1998	64:Anchor Books	68:read	69:2015-07-03	67:4/5	70:Fabulous writing. Really engrossing.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38447
5:038464992	6:gr-38464992	3:Big Damn Hero (Firefly, #1)	4:book review	60:Big Damn Hero (Firefly, #1)	61:James Lovegrove	62:2018	64:Titan Books	68:read	69:2020-08-29	63:9781785658266	67:2/5	70:The story's limited focus dragged out slowly and used nonsense to justify hiding information. The character voices were decent for Mal, Jayne and Zoe, but the rest of crew missed the mark wildly. This story is safe to skip.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38464992
5:038479272	6:gr-38479272	3:Trouble's Child: An Angela Constantine Novella	4:book review	60:Trouble's Child: An Angela Constantine Novella	61:Terry Goodkind	62:2018	64:Skyhorse	68:read	69:2022-12-13	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38479272
5:038532434	6:gr-38532434	3:The Ultimate RPG Character Backstory Guide: Prompts and Activities to Create the Most Interesting Story for Your Character (Ultimate Role Playing Game Series)	4:book review	60:The Ultimate RPG Character Backstory Guide: Prompts and Activities to Create the Most Interesting Story for Your Character (Ultimate Role Playing Game Series)	61:James D’Amato	62:2018	64:Adams Media	68:read	69:2022-03-18	63:9781507208373	67:4/5	70:This is great reference material for character creation for RPGs, but also for books. I'll be referring to it often.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38532434
5:000038619	6:gr-38619	3:Magic Bites (Kate Daniels, #1)	4:book review	60:Magic Bites (Kate Daniels, #1)	61:Ilona Andrews	62:2007	64:Ace	68:read	69:2017-08-27	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38619
5:003862437	6:gr-3862437	3:Doctor Who: Judgement of the Judoon	4:book review	60:Doctor Who: Judgement of the Judoon	61:Colin Brake	62:2009	64:BBC Books	68:read	69:2014-05-30	63:9781846076398	67:4/5	70:Suprising character depth make this one of the best Doctor Who stories I've read.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3862437
5:000386299	6:gr-386299	3:The Old Man and the Sea	4:book review	60:The Old Man and the Sea	61:Ernest Hemingway	62:1995	64:Scribner	68:read	69:1994-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/386299
5:000003869	6:gr-3869	3:A Brief History of Time	4:book review	60:A Brief History of Time	61:Stephen Hawking	62:1998	64:Bantam Books	68:read	69:1995-01-01	63:9780553380163	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3869
5:000003876	6:gr-3876	3:The Sun Also Rises	4:book review	60:The Sun Also Rises	61:Ernest Hemingway	62:1957	64:Pan Books	68:read	69:2003-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/3876
5:038771006	6:gr-38771006	3:The Right to Arm Bears (Threadbare #3)	4:book review	60:The Right to Arm Bears (Threadbare #3)	61:Andrew Seiple	62:2018	68:read	69:2022-03-29	67:2/5	70:I think the charm may have worn off on this gimmick. I find myself tuning out for passages and not caring enough to go back and re-listen. The direction of the story is interesting in theory, and the characters are all charming in their own way, but it just feels haphazard. I'm not really invested in what happens next and despite a lot of action there isn't much drama.\n\nI'm not sure if there are more books in the series or not, but I think I'm done.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/38771006
5:039196519	6:gr-39196519	3:Cook It in Your Dutch Oven: 150 Foolproof Recipes Tailor-Made for Your Kitchen's Most Versatile Pot	4:book review	60:Cook It in Your Dutch Oven: 150 Foolproof Recipes Tailor-Made for Your Kitchen's Most Versatile Pot	61:America's Test Kitchen	62:2018	64:America's Test Kitchen	68:read	69:2019-04-28	63:9781945256561	67:4/5	70:Some fantastic recipes in here that really show off the creativity of a Dutch oven. You know you're in for something special when a recipe calls for flipping the lid upside down. \n\nThe into has a nice guide to Dutch ovens as well. Glad I picked it up from the library. Many note cards have been filled!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/39196519
5:039395857	6:gr-39395857	3:The Raven Tower	4:book review	60:The Raven Tower	61:Ann Leckie	62:2019	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2019-07-28	63:9780356506999	67:5/5	70:I don't typically read the last page of a book with shivers, but Anne Leckie managed it here. Well done.\n\nAt the start I thought the tense choice was a gimmick. I'm glad I waited long enough to figure out why it was being used and what it meant. This is a fantastic read.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/39395857
5:000395962	6:gr-395962	3:Kushiel's Chosen (Phèdre's Trilogy, #2)	4:book review	60:Kushiel's Chosen (Phèdre's Trilogy, #2)	61:Jacqueline Carey	62:2003	64:Tom Doherty Associates TOR Fantasy	68:read	69:2008-01-01	63:9780765345042	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/395962
5:039692401	6:gr-39692401	3:Wabi Sabi: Japanese Wisdom for a Perfectly Imperfect Life	4:book review	60:Wabi Sabi: Japanese Wisdom for a Perfectly Imperfect Life	61:Beth Kempton	62:2018	64:Piatkus	68:read	69:2022-07-10	63:0349420998	67:3/5	70:This was really quite enjoyable. Some have criticized the structure of it, or the fact that it seems self-serving, but I think it's honest to itself. Beth Kempton is a self-help author and this book reads like such. But that doesn't mean she misses the mark on describing wabi sabi or how it integrates into the lessons she imparts. I found her personal anecdotes helpful in bridging that gap. What's left is not a pure sociological view at an element of Japanese culture, nor is it entirely a self-help book in the style of Marie Kondo, nor is it a travel journal, but by weaving elements of all three it is something imperfect and beautiful.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/39692401
5:039697206	6:gr-39697206	3:Ed Mastery: The Standard Unix Text Editor (IT Mastery)	4:book review	60:Ed Mastery: The Standard Unix Text Editor (IT Mastery)	61:Michael W. Lucas	62:2018	64:Tilted Windmill Press	68:read	69:2018-01-01	67:5/5	70:April fools joke or not, this book is seriously useful. Even though I will likely never use ed(1) directly on purpose, I'm now comfortable enough to get by. More importantly, I discovered a lot of the underlying logic behind vim's Ex mode, g/re/p, and sed that weren't as intuitive before. Michael's tone and humor kept what could have been a very boring topic wildly engaging. I was sharing snippets with people all throughout my read and even went back to give the regex section a second pass.\n\nIf this book has come across your path, do yourself a favor and pick it up. It's worth every penny.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/39697206
5:000397156	6:gr-397156	3:SSN: A Strategy Guide to Submarine Warfare	4:book review	60:SSN: A Strategy Guide to Submarine Warfare	61:Tom Clancy	62:2000	64:Berkley	68:read	69:1999-01-01	63:9780425173534	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/397156
5:000397157	6:gr-397157	3:Paddle-to-the-Sea	4:book review	60:Paddle-to-the-Sea	61:Holling Clancy Holling	62:1980	64:Turtleback Books	68:read	63:9780808551515	67:5/5	70:Read this growing up and built a little boat with my dad to let loose in a stream. I wonder if I'll encounter it again one day.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/397157
5:039739209	6:gr-39739209	3:Ms. Marvel, Vol. 10: Time and Again	4:book review	60:Ms. Marvel, Vol. 10: Time and Again	61:G. Willow Wilson	62:2019	64:Marvel Universe	68:read	69:2022-01-03	63:9781302912697	67:3/5	70:Well, that wraps up G Willow Wilson's time as writer for Ms. Marvel and I have to say I'm impressed. Overall this was a great series and a great introduction to an awesome new super hero. This last book reconnected some friends and explored some fun next-steps in their lives. There wasn't anything groundbreaking, but it still felt like a nice send off.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/39739209
5:039830001	6:gr-39830001	3:Hand Sewing Magic: Essential Know-How for Hand Stitching--*10 Easy, Creative Projects *Master Tension and Other Techniques * With Pro Tips, Tricks, and Troubleshooting	4:book review	60:Hand Sewing Magic: Essential Know-How for Hand Stitching--*10 Easy, Creative Projects *Master Tension and Other Techniques * With Pro Tips, Tricks, and Troubleshooting	61:Lynn Krawczyk	62:2018	64:Quarry Books	68:read	69:2019-09-09	63:9781589239685	67:4/5	70:This book had a lot of overlap with another I read recently: [b:Slow Stitch: Mindful and Contemplative Textile Art|24886854|Slow Stitch  Mindful and Contemplative Textile Art|Claire Wellesley-Smith|https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/books/1438047849l/24886854._SX50_.jpg|44535292]. I think the instructional introductory method of Hand Sewing Magic was better, though, and less focused on the philosophy.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/39830001
5:000400869	6:gr-400869	3:The Kalevala	4:book review	60:The Kalevala	61:Elias Lönnrot	62:1999	64:Oxford University Press	68:read	69:2011-11-17	63:9780192835703	67:4/5	70:I think this is one of those books that needs a few reads with a few years between them. It reminds me of the Odyssey quite a bit, and there are some obvious parallels in the story. It's wrong to think of this as a derivative work, though. It may share some style and elements with it, but the Kalevala is uniquely Finnish. If you are the type of person who enjoys this type of work then don't miss out. There's more than enough unique material to keep your attention.\n\nI can't say much with confidence after this first reading, but I will make note of the really interesting spirituality of the book. While there are many vaguely Christian notions (and a few overt ones), there is still an incredibly strong sense of the earlier pagan animism that is beautifully tied up in it. For that aspect alone I think this book is worthy of a lot of attention from those of you who are interested in comparative religion.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/400869
5:040089999	6:gr-40089999	3:Galaxy Outlaws: The Complete Black Ocean Mobius Missions (Black Ocean, #1-16.5)	4:book review	60:Galaxy Outlaws: The Complete Black Ocean Mobius Missions (Black Ocean, #1-16.5)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2018	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-07	67:5/5	70:The series bills itself as a bit of a Firefly adventure and I can see that, but by the time this first series of missions ends it's significantly more developed than that show (and movie) ever were. The world building is rich and varied. The characters are all breathing and vibrant. It's a joy to spend time here.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40089999
5:040146937	6:gr-40146937	3:Fat Quarter: One-Piece Projects: 25 Projects to Make from Short Lengths of Fabric	4:book review	60:Fat Quarter: One-Piece Projects: 25 Projects to Make from Short Lengths of Fabric	61:Tina Barrett	62:2018	64:Vista Partners Inc.	68:read	69:2019-04-28	63:9781784944209	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40146937
5:040165340	6:gr-40165340	3:Call of the Dragon (Dragon Riders of Elantia, #1)	4:book review	60:Call of the Dragon (Dragon Riders of Elantia, #1)	61:Jessica Drake	62:2018	64:Dynamo Press	68:read	69:2021-04-14	67:3/5	70:Some of my other audiobooks are quite heavy and long and I needed a light-hearted break. Call of the Dragon fit in nicely. There's enough of the story that is automatically familiar to genre readers that it is an easy listen while doing other things, like cooking or working. The characters were fun, the reading suitable. I wasn't surprised by the twists but still managed to have a nice time. I've got a few more of these in the queue. I think I'll save them for when I need a break.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40165340
5:040188708	6:gr-40188708	3:Changeling (Sorcery and Society, #1)	4:book review	60:Changeling (Sorcery and Society, #1)	61:Molly Harper	62:2018	64:NYLA	68:read	69:2019-02-23	67:4/5	70:Surprisingly strong! I'll have to read more in this series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40188708
5:000402045	6:gr-402045	3:The Mists of Avalon (Avalon, #1)	4:book review	60:The Mists of Avalon (Avalon, #1)	61:Marion Zimmer Bradley	62:1984	64:Ballantine Books	68:read	69:2008-01-01	63:9780345350497	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/402045
5:040205388	6:gr-40205388	3:Flight of the Dragon (Dragon Riders of Elantia, #2)	4:book review	60:Flight of the Dragon (Dragon Riders of Elantia, #2)	61:Jessica Drake	62:2018	64:Dynamo Press	68:read	69:2021-05-30	67:1/5	70:The second book of the Dragon Riders of Elantia was a let-down. It ends with a "to be continued" at an arbitrary point. As a book it is a failure. There is no comprehensive sense of unit to the content, nor any rising tension and relief, to say anything of resolution. "The characters did some things," is about the best that can be said of it.\n\nAnd while we're talking about the characters, they're all quite dumb, especially our heroine. She revels in her snarkiness but crumples before any actual authority. She bites her tongue and seeths or else boldly runs into action without a moment consideration. The number of times she's rescued by pure chance strains suspension of disbelief. Also, her relationships are shallow things without any real sense behind them.\n\nI have the 3rd one because it was on sale from Audible, but I'm not sure I'll get around to it anytime soon.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40205388
5:040229418	6:gr-40229418	3:Miss Peregrine's Home For Peculiar Children (Miss Peregrine's Peculiar Children, #1)	4:book review	60:Miss Peregrine's Home For Peculiar Children (Miss Peregrine's Peculiar Children, #1)	61:Ransom Riggs	62:2011	64:Quirk Books	68:read	69:2018-08-06	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40229418
5:040280403	6:gr-40280403	3:Ghostwater (Cradle, #5)	4:book review	60:Ghostwater (Cradle, #5)	61:Will Wight	62:2018	64:Hidden Gnome Publishing	68:read	69:2020-03-28	67:4/5	70:Okay, this book is back on track.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40280403
5:040280648	6:gr-40280648	3:Mavericks (Expeditionary Force, #6)	4:book review	60:Mavericks (Expeditionary Force, #6)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2018	68:read	69:2018-12-03	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40280648
5:000402843	6:gr-402843	3:Zen Mind, Beginner's Mind: Informal Talks on Zen Meditation and Practice	4:book review	60:Zen Mind, Beginner's Mind: Informal Talks on Zen Meditation and Practice	61:Shunryu Suzuki	62:1970	64:Weatherhill	68:read	69:2011-01-01	63:9780834800793	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/402843
5:000040395	6:gr-40395	3:A Princess of Mars (Barsoom, #1)	4:book review	60:A Princess of Mars (Barsoom, #1)	61:Edgar Rice Burroughs	62:2007	64:Penguin Books	68:read	69:2012-04-30	63:9780143104889	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40395
5:040502274	6:gr-40502274	3:Underlord (Cradle, #6)	4:book review	60:Underlord (Cradle, #6)	61:Will Wight	62:2019	64:Hidden Gnome Publishing	68:read	69:2020-03-30	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40502274
5:040537854	6:gr-40537854	3:Sci-Phi: Science Fiction as Philosophy	4:book review	60:Sci-Phi: Science Fiction as Philosophy	61:David Kyle Johnson	62:2018	64:The Great Courses	68:read	69:2022-08-01	67:3/5	70:There's not nearly enough philosophy OF science fiction in these lectures. Instead it's a survey of philosophies with examples in sci-fi.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40537854
5:040582131	6:gr-40582131	3:The Sidekicks Initiative: A Comedy Superhero Adventure (Sidekicks Initiative, #1)	4:book review	60:The Sidekicks Initiative: A Comedy Superhero Adventure (Sidekicks Initiative, #1)	61:Barry J. Hutchison	62:2018	64:Zertex Media Ltd	68:read	69:2020-04-25	67:5/5	70:Really satisfying comedy adventure. It got some out-loud laughing from me	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40582131
5:040604754	6:gr-40604754	3:Heir to the Empire (Star Wars: The Thrawn Trilogy, #1)	4:book review	60:Heir to the Empire (Star Wars: The Thrawn Trilogy, #1)	61:Timothy Zahn	62:2011	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2020-01-01	67:5/5	70:Now that all of the core Star Wars films have been released I can now say with confidence that both the prequels and sequels are nothing but poor fan fiction. Yes, George Lucas is a fan boy of his own legacy.\n\nInstead, I'm reaffirming the truth, that Timothy Zahn wrote the canonical follow up to the Star Wars trilogy. Heir to the Empire is a brilliant start introducing both Mara Jade and Admiral Thrawn. The characters are all vibrant. They grow. They move the story without unnecessary tricks and twists. Moist importantly, they are true to their natures.\n\nI'll be rereading the others soon to refresh in my mind the true conclusion to the Skywalker saga. I highly recommend you do the same.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40604754
5:040616782	6:gr-40616782	3:Symphony of the Wind (The Raincatcher's Ballad, #1)	4:book review	60:Symphony of the Wind (The Raincatcher's Ballad, #1)	61:Steven McKinnon	62:2018	64:KDP Print	68:read	69:2019-11-25	63:9781718600690	67:1/5	70:DNF. I listened to this from Audible and I'm returning it. The reader chose exttremely odd voices for each of the main characters. They were at odds with the descriptions of their voices, ignored regional accents that were clear in the text itself, and just sounded ridiculous. It then became clear the reader wasn't paying attention to the text at all. He whispered sentences that were "exclaimed". He broke up sentences oddly in the middle because, I can only assume, of a line break. It was just bad.\n\nI suspect this story is decent. I'll have to try again with the text. For now this gets 1 star for the audible version.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40616782
5:040666927	6:gr-40666927	3:Might of the Dragon (Dragon Riders of Elantia, #3)	4:book review	60:Might of the Dragon (Dragon Riders of Elantia, #3)	61:Jessica Drake	62:2018	64:Dynamo Press	68:read	69:2021-09-26	67:1/5	70:Okay, I give up. These books are not any good. This one barely had any dragons despite the name.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40666927
5:040698027	6:gr-40698027	3:A Boy and His Dog at the End of the World	4:book review	60:A Boy and His Dog at the End of the World	61:C.A. Fletcher	62:2019	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2020-08-01	63:9780316449458	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40698027
5:040718726	6:gr-40718726	3:Genghis Khan and the Making of the Modern World	4:book review	60:Genghis Khan and the Making of the Modern World	61:Jack Weatherford	62:2018	64:Broadway Books	68:read	69:2021-12-29	67:2/5	70:I was disappointed in the "making of the modern world" aspect of the book. Yes, it was a thorough biography of Genghis Khan for the first half of the book. The second half covered the remainder of the Mongol empire's story nicely, but the implications of how it formed the world we have today were afterthoughts, implied, or omitted. The treatment of the Chinese by the Tibetan Buddhists during the late Mongol occupation is a fantastic example. It sets up the reflexive attitudes that underpin modern China's relationship with Tibet, but that line of thought isn't pursued. There's a thousand other places where implications seem on the edge of being discussed only for us to hop back to the steppe and begin anew with another family member's story.\n\nUltimately that deficiency is one of expectation from the title, not of the book's actual substance. Even so, it lowered my enjoyment. I spent the whole book in anticipation only to reach the awkward Afterward in disappointment.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40718726
5:040864002	6:gr-40864002	3:A Psalm for the Wild-Built (Monk & Robot, #1)	4:book review	60:A Psalm for the Wild-Built (Monk & Robot, #1)	61:Becky  Chambers	62:2021	64:Tordotcom	68:read	69:2022-01-15	67:5/5	70:This book is such a joyful, peaceful journey of the heart. I loved the monk and I loved the robot and I want to spend more time with them both. \n\nM: "How does the idea of maybe being meaningless sit well with you?"\n\nR: "Because I know that no matter what, I'm wonderful."	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40864002
5:040864030	6:gr-40864030	3:A Prayer for the Crown-Shy (Monk & Robot, #2)	4:book review	60:A Prayer for the Crown-Shy (Monk & Robot, #2)	61:Becky  Chambers	62:2022	64:Tordotcom	68:read	69:2022-08-14	67:3/5	70:Not as good as book 1, but still an enjoyable time with sibling Dex and Mosscap.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40864030
5:040874032	6:gr-40874032	3:Vicious (Villains, #1)	4:book review	60:Vicious (Villains, #1)	61:V.E. Schwab	62:2013	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2023-11-14	67:2/5	70:I struggled a lot through this one. I never connected with the characters at all or grew invested in their desires and needs. As a result the action always felt at a distance. The nature of EOs and their creation wasn't particularly interesting or novel, nor did it cross the threshold of esoteric action which warranted suspension of disbelief.\n\nThe writing itself is perfectly cromulent. I have no specific issues with characterization, lack of roundness, issues of voice, description, or any such failings. All the ingredients where there from an author that clearly knows the craft well. It just didn't land for me.\n\nBased on the overall reviews, and those of people I know and trust, I'm the odd-ball here. You'll probably like it.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40874032
5:040874079	6:gr-40874079	3:Orphan X (Orphan X, #1)	4:book review	60:Orphan X (Orphan X, #1)	61:Gregg Andrew Hurwitz	62:2016	64:Minotaur Books	68:read	69:2022-12-27	67:2/5	70:Pretty tiresome. Mix and match Jason Bourne-esque super-agent acting as a savior for the little guy while being judge, jury, and executioner. No personality to speak of. No reason for his background. No reason for the plot of the story. Lots of him being a badass cause he knows all the things. Mary-sue and boring.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40874079
5:040909836	6:gr-40909836	3:Level Five	4:book review	60:Level Five	61:William Ledbetter	62:2018	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2019-12-10	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/40909836
5:041016100	6:gr-41016100	3:The Coming Storm	4:book review	60:The Coming Storm	61:Michael   Lewis	62:2018	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2018-09-16	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41016100
5:041033158	6:gr-41033158	3:The Wandering Inn (The Wandering Inn, #1)	4:book review	60:The Wandering Inn (The Wandering Inn, #1)	61:Pirateaba	62:2018	68:read	69:2019-11-05	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41033158
5:041180829	6:gr-41180829	3:The Wandering Inn: Fae and Fare: Volume 2 (The Wandering Inn, #2)	4:book review	60:The Wandering Inn: Fae and Fare: Volume 2 (The Wandering Inn, #2)	61:Pirateaba	62:2019	68:read	69:2020-07-29	67:5/5	70:I love these characters. I love the inn. I love the endless story that draws you in like a warm hug. I know there are other books written, but I really enjoy the audio versions. I hope the next book gets recorded soon.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41180829
5:041211815	6:gr-41211815	3:Aftershocks (The Palladium Wars #1)	4:book review	60:Aftershocks (The Palladium Wars #1)	61:Marko Kloos	62:2019	64:47North	68:read	69:2021-03-29	63:9781542043540	67:4/5	70:This was a lot of fun. I'm not sure where the story is going yet and the book ended without any sort of resolution. My guess is that this was split in half and the next book should have been bundled together with this one.\n\nSadly I'm going to have to wait to get to book two. I've been listening to this on Audible and for some reason the publisher decided to change readers in book 2. The reviews are understandably negative as a result. Publishers, if you're reading this, don't do that. Seriously.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41211815
5:041241968	6:gr-41241968	3:The Wandering Inn: Volume 3 (The Wandering Inn, #3)	4:book review	60:The Wandering Inn: Volume 3 (The Wandering Inn, #3)	61:Pirateaba	62:2020	64:Pirateaba	68:read	69:2021-05-04	67:5/5	70:Another joy to read. I want to pick up the next one right now, and I could do so if I didn't absolutely love the audio so much. I'll try to wait for the next one on Audible.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41241968
5:000413926	6:gr-413926	3:Will Shortz Presents Ultimate Sudoku	4:book review	60:Will Shortz Presents Ultimate Sudoku	61:Will Shortz	62:2006	64:St. Martin's Griffin	68:read	69:2004-01-01	63:9780312345631	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/413926
5:000414001	6:gr-414001	3:Competing on Analytics	4:book review	60:Competing on Analytics	61:Thomas H. Davenport	62:2007	64:Harvard	68:read	69:2014-01-01	63:9781422103326	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/414001
5:041477610	6:gr-41477610	3:The Wandering Inn: Volume 4 (The Wandering Inn, #4)	4:book review	60:The Wandering Inn: Volume 4 (The Wandering Inn, #4)	61:Pirateaba	64:Pirateaba	68:read	69:2021-08-08	67:5/5	70:With so many characters meeting each other, reunions and first introductions, it was exciting to see how the characters played off one another. I loved the flashback chapters too. A very weird ending gives some hints to the future. I hope I don't have to wait too long for #5.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41477610
5:041490566	6:gr-41490566	3:Chroma Venture (The Spiral Wars #5)	4:book review	60:Chroma Venture (The Spiral Wars #5)	61:Joel Shepherd	68:read	69:2021-10-02	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41490566
5:000414999	6:gr-414999	3:Childhood's End	4:book review	60:Childhood's End	61:Arthur C. Clarke	62:1987	64:Del Rey Books	68:read	69:2010-01-01	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/414999
5:041574630	6:gr-41574630	3:I'm From the Sun: The Gustafer Yellowgold Story	4:book review	60:I'm From the Sun: The Gustafer Yellowgold Story	61:Morgan   Taylor	62:2018	64:Audible	68:read	69:2019-10-04	63:9781721357253	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41574630
5:041716919	6:gr-41716919	3:Jade War (The Green Bone Saga, #2)	4:book review	60:Jade War (The Green Bone Saga, #2)	61:Fonda Lee	62:2019	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2023-01-06	63:9780316440929	67:5/5	70:Great continuation to a powerful series. It goes places you won't expect.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41716919
5:000041811	6:gr-41811	3:The Caves of Steel (Robot, #1)	4:book review	60:The Caves of Steel (Robot, #1)	61:Isaac Asimov	62:1997	64:Voyager	68:read	69:1998-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41811
5:041814120	6:gr-41814120	3:Wayward Saint: Mission 1 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Wayward Saint: Mission 1 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2018	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-25	63:9781643550077	67:4/5	70:It was fun to see Esper taking off on her own. The way things don't go according to plan is par for the course for the black ocean. A new fun adventure begins.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41814120
5:041839377	6:gr-41839377	3:Behind Blue Skies: Mission 2 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Behind Blue Skies: Mission 2 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2018	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-25	63:9781643550091	67:4/5	70:This weird back-water planet has all sorts of creepiness going for it. The injustices pile up and it's difficult not to yell at the characters at times. Some tense moments there too.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41839377
5:000041865	6:gr-41865	3:Twilight (The Twilight Saga, #1)	4:book review	60:Twilight (The Twilight Saga, #1)	61:Stephenie Meyer	62:2006	64:Little, Brown and Company	68:read	69:2011-07-01	63:9780316015844	67:1/5	70:The emptiness of this book was astounding. I didn't really care for the films, but I thought there might be more depth in the book. I was wrong. There was an unprecedentedly vast horror of cliche and petty manipulation. Pages upon pages describing the perfection of Edward and when it comes time to tell us about our main character, the description falters. Why? Because the author has determined to let her readers step into that role and fill it with their own sympathetic insecurities. \n\nWhereas that may work for a teenage girl, I found it endlessly annoying. I never fell into the story, and that is its greatest failing. So many of the trivial things I would normally let slide in a book with my profound ability to suspend disbelief were shockingly forefront.\n\nThis rant could go on, but I'm beginning to make myself angry, and that should never happen in a review.\n\nIn short: if you're a teenage girl, pick it up. Otherwise...	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41865
5:041921362	6:gr-41921362	3:Break the Chain: Mission 4 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Break the Chain: Mission 4 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2018	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-25	67:1/5	70:Oh wow. This book felt a bit like a flashback episode. I didn't care for it for its own sake, and I really don't like the direction things took at the end.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41921362
5:041921367	6:gr-41921367	3:House of the Orion Sun: Mission 3 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:House of the Orion Sun: Mission 3 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2018	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-25	63:9781643550107	67:3/5	70:This book took a bit of a turn. I had a bit of trouble buying just how deeply Esper lets herself slip into the roles on her mission. It didn't really resonate with the hard choices we've seen her make in the past. Is it due to the tomb of bleeding thoughts, perhaps? Time will tell.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41921367
