5:041970691	6:gr-41970691	3:The 3-Day Effect	4:book review	60:The 3-Day Effect	61:NOT A BOOK	62:2018	64:Audio Studios	68:read	69:2019-05-11	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/41970691
5:042036538	6:gr-42036538	3:Gideon the Ninth (The Locked Tomb, #1)	4:book review	60:Gideon the Ninth (The Locked Tomb, #1)	61:Tamsyn Muir	62:2019	64:Tor	68:read	69:2020-08-09	63:9781250313195	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42036538
5:042092378	6:gr-42092378	3:One More Last Time (The Good Guys, #1)	4:book review	60:One More Last Time (The Good Guys, #1)	61:Eric Ugland	62:2018	64:Air Quotes Publishing	68:read	69:2021-02-04	67:2/5	70:Another litrpg another difficult review. Eric Ugland's story takes a different tack than most, inserting a colorful character with a shady past into a game world rather than the geek du jour. I had high hopes that the lead's desire for a peaceful life to re-start would take us in interesting directions. Sadly with a few minor exceptions the output was pretty boilerplate. "I don't want to be a hero," became code for a false modesty as our protagonist quickly gained unbalanced abilities and worked miracles. The result is an average undertaking.\n\nIf you adore litrpg you will probably like this. If you are like me and roll your eyes everytime someone busts out their character sheet, skip it.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42092378
5:042096891	6:gr-42096891	3:Wishes and Wellingtons (Wishes and Wellingtons, #1)	4:book review	60:Wishes and Wellingtons (Wishes and Wellingtons, #1)	61:Julie Berry	62:2018	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2020-04-03	67:2/5	70:There's some nice setting trope, but I failed to suspend my disbelief, not in the fantastic but in the characters. It didn't land.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42096891
5:000004214	6:gr-4214	3:Life of Pi	4:book review	60:Life of Pi	61:Yann Martel	62:2006	64:Seal Books	68:read	69:2012-01-01	63:9780770430078	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4214
5:042187371	6:gr-42187371	3:Lullaby	4:book review	60:Lullaby	61:Jonathan Maberry	62:2018	68:read	69:2019-02-24	67:3/5	70:This is a good ghost story. It deserves some good ratings. But the stuff that happens in it are making me unfairly take a star away.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42187371
5:042259962	6:gr-42259962	3:Make Me No Grave	4:book review	60:Make Me No Grave	61:Hayley Stone	62:2018	64:Aethon Books	68:read	69:2019-08-21	63:9781949890006	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42259962
5:042267952	6:gr-42267952	3:Into the Labyrinth (Mage Errant, #1)	4:book review	60:Into the Labyrinth (Mage Errant, #1)	61:John Bierce	62:2018	68:read	69:2021-08-30	67:3/5	70:Fairly formulaic and quite a bit of exposition, but a nice simple read.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42267952
5:042290337	6:gr-42290337	3:git commit murder	4:book review	60:git commit murder	61:Michael Warren Lucas	62:2017	64:Tilted Windmill Press	68:read	69:2018-06-18	63:9781642350128	67:5/5	70:This is a book for a very specific audience, but for that audience it is pure gold.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42290337
5:042361141	6:gr-42361141	3:Rivals! Frenemies Who Changed the World (Rivals #1)	4:book review	60:Rivals! Frenemies Who Changed the World (Rivals #1)	61:Scott McCormick	62:2018	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2019-12-31	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42361141
5:042385018	6:gr-42385018	3:Minimum Wage Magic (DFZ, #1)	4:book review	60:Minimum Wage Magic (DFZ, #1)	61:Rachel Aaron	62:2018	64:Aaron/Bach	68:read	69:2020-09-01	67:3/5	70:I was surprised when the book opened up in the Detroit Free Zone (DFZ). I knew that setting! Had I read this before? But no, I'd tried out the first of Rachel Aaron's other series with Nice Dragons Finish Last. This felt similar in tone and was a pretty enjoyable little adventure.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42385018
5:000042434	6:gr-42434	3:Sandworms of Dune (Dune, #8)	4:book review	60:Sandworms of Dune (Dune, #8)	61:Brian Herbert	62:2007	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2019-10-20	63:9780765312938	67:1/5	70:This is a terrible ending to the epic. The pacing is terribly drawn out. The plot twists are obvious. The brilliant characters are suddenly idiots who don't have backup plans. The resolution between the enemies is utter nonsense.\n\nI know they claim this is based upon Frank Herbert's notes for the series but the heavy leaning on the butlarian jihad reads like Brian and Kevin trying to make their prequels meaningful. If that was really the direction being planned Frank would have had some sign in an earlier story.\n\nThe Ghola plots we're a cheap way to get readers in with familiar characters despite having no real purpose. In the end, the action of the main characters was irrelevant. The plans and plotting had no bearing on the outcome at any level. The extended Hollywood ending was trite as well.\n\nIf you, like me, loved the Dune books so much that the cliffhanger after book 6 made you want to read these last two to wrap things up... don't. Just don't. Your musings and daydreams are better.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42434
5:000424340	6:gr-424340	3:Zen in the Martial Arts	4:book review	60:Zen in the Martial Arts	61:Joe Hyams	62:1982	64:Bantam	68:read	69:2021-12-27	63:9780553275599	67:4/5	70:This short volume packed in a lot of key zen lessons through anecdotes, quotes, and examples. Like many books on the subject there's a lot of time spent explaining what the book is not. Even so, there's a wealth of lessons worth learning.\n\nIf you're a student of Zen this may bring you a new perspective or help give clarity to certain topics. If you're new to Zen but enjoy martial arts there's a nice introduction to the topic and broad overview. If you know of neither there's some interesting anecdotes that makes for good storytelling. If you are a student of both disciplines this is an inspirational read that will help you refocus on your inner path.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/424340
5:042631204	6:gr-42631204	3:Íslenska fyrir alla	4:book review	60:Íslenska fyrir alla	61:Sólborg Jónsdóttir	62:2011	68:read	69:2019-03-13	63:9789935902849	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42631204
5:000042632	6:gr-42632	3:Thirst	4:book review	60:Thirst	61:Mary Oliver	62:2006	64:Beacon Press	68:read	69:2018-11-04	63:9780807068960	67:5/5	70:I adore Mary Oliver's words	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42632
5:004266110	6:gr-4266110	3:Full Share (Golden Age of the Solar Clipper, #3)	4:book review	60:Full Share (Golden Age of the Solar Clipper, #3)	61:Nathan Lowell	62:2008	68:read	69:2014-09-11	67:4/5	70:Wow, things actually happened in this book! I mean, not a lot of things, but compared to the rest of the series thus far this book was action packed.\n\nI'm still a fan of the series and its lightheartedness.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4266110
5:042769202	6:gr-42769202	3:Starsight (Skyward, #2)	4:book review	60:Starsight (Skyward, #2)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2019	64:Orion Publishing Co	68:read	69:2019-12-05	63:9781473217904	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42769202
5:042839296	6:gr-42839296	3:Hollow Kingdom (Hollow Kingdom, #1)	4:book review	60:Hollow Kingdom (Hollow Kingdom, #1)	61:Kira Jane Buxton	62:2019	64:Grand Central Publishing	68:read	69:2023-07-31	63:9781538745823	67:3/5	70:The POV voice and language really gave life to a book with an astounding number of similarities to Wayward Pines. I was a little surprised just how good the use of language is throughout the story, especially in the vingettes between main character chapters. If you're a fan of zombie stories, like talking animals, or have a place in your heart for irreverent POV characters then give this a shot.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42839296
5:042844512	6:gr-42844512	3:Renegades (Expeditionary Force, #7)	4:book review	60:Renegades (Expeditionary Force, #7)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2018	68:read	69:2019-05-24	67:4/5	70:Skippy books are always fun	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42844512
5:042950440	6:gr-42950440	3:Heaven's River (Bobiverse, #4)	4:book review	60:Heaven's River (Bobiverse, #4)	61:Dennis E. Taylor	62:2020	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2020-11-09	67:3/5	70:The new themes introduced in Heaven's River give it an edge in what might otherwise seem a bit of a repetition on earlier works. Yes, we have Bob getting involved in the local alien species lives, but this time it's for a rescue mission. Meanwhile the B-plot is diving deeper into replicative drift, politics, individualism, and even the question of the soul (as viewed through quantum mechanics and information theory). The writing is good and scratches the science itch nicely. The parts that are glossed over are chosen with care so that we can sink our teeth into the theme more dramatically. A nice read overall.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/42950440
5:000430788	6:gr-430788	3:Goblin Market: A Tale of Two Sisters	4:book review	60:Goblin Market: A Tale of Two Sisters	61:Christina Rossetti	62:1997	64:Chronicle Books Llc	68:read	69:2011-01-01	63:9780811816496	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/430788
5:000043545	6:gr-43545	3:The Once and Future King (The Once and Future King, #1-4)	4:book review	60:The Once and Future King (The Once and Future King, #1-4)	61:T.H. White	62:1987	64:Ace	68:read	69:2006-01-01	63:9780441627400	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43545
5:043587154	6:gr-43587154	3:Jade City (The Green Bone Saga, #1)	4:book review	60:Jade City (The Green Bone Saga, #1)	61:Fonda Lee	62:2018	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2022-10-19	63:9780316440882	66:friend-recommended	67:5/5	70:A brilliant start to an epic series. Set in a near-present alternate world in an East-meets-West city filled with warring clans and the shadow of colonialism all around, this is a truly massive undertaking. Sporting complex world building and a vibrant cast this first book does an incredible job taking us through thrilling action and the depths of despair as felt through family legacy. It's some of the best low-fantasy I've read in years.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43587154
5:043601931	6:gr-43601931	3:Hemlock and Hedge (The Witches of Wormwood #0.5)	4:book review	60:Hemlock and Hedge (The Witches of Wormwood #0.5)	61:Silver Nord	62:2019	64:Amazon Digital Services	68:read	69:2022-01-15	67:2/5	70:It's been a while since I read the first book in this series but I get the feeling this short story is actually just a sample from that book. If not it fails as a story in itself, leaving off abruptly and offering no sense of beginning, middle, and end. But Ruby Loren's writing is still good (even if her character names are ridiculously on the nose) and her small town of Wormwood feels alive.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43601931
5:043613126	6:gr-43613126	3:Zero G (The Zero Chronicles, #1)	4:book review	60:Zero G (The Zero Chronicles, #1)	61:Dan Wells	62:2018	64:Audible  Studios	68:read	69:2019-01-06	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43613126
5:000436148	6:gr-436148	3:Mary Poppins in Cherry Tree Lane (Mary Poppins, #5)	4:book review	60:Mary Poppins in Cherry Tree Lane (Mary Poppins, #5)	61:P.L. Travers	62:1983	64:Dell	68:read	69:2002-01-01	63:9780440457930	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/436148
5:000043615	6:gr-43615	3:The Gunslinger (The Dark Tower, #1)	4:book review	60:The Gunslinger (The Dark Tower, #1)	61:Stephen King	62:2003	64:Plume	68:read	69:2002-01-01	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43615
5:043622036	6:gr-43622036	3:Mandrake and a Murder (The Witches of Wormwood Mysteries #1)	4:book review	60:Mandrake and a Murder (The Witches of Wormwood Mysteries #1)	61:Silver Nord	62:2019	68:read	69:2019-10-06	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43622036
5:000043641	6:gr-43641	3:Water for Elephants	4:book review	60:Water for Elephants	61:Sara Gruen	62:2007	64:Algonquin Books	68:read	69:2012-04-15	63:9781565125605	67:3/5	70:I picked this up for free from the Amazon Lending Library. I recently read Night Circus and thought I might enjoy one more circus related book before I head back into genre fiction once again.\n\nThe writing was solid, the characters each believable and likable, and the story interesting. The book's strength came from a wonderfully researched circus train and a dismally realistic portrayal of the despair of old age. Each world grounded the other in reality and made this story something special.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43641
5:043670629	6:gr-43670629	3:Fallen (Alex Verus, #10)	4:book review	60:Fallen (Alex Verus, #10)	61:Benedict Jacka	62:2019	64:Ace	68:read	69:2022-08-04	63:9780440000587	67:5/5	70:One of the dangers of long book series is when the fall into the trap of episodic TV where things end pretty much where they started. Maybe a new character is introduced, but the protagonists have grown only in experience and nothing really changes the status quo. The Alex Verus series feels a bit like this early on. Books progress and the list of Alex's enemies grows. He's forced to make hard choices and walk a difficult ethical path, but he himself remains basically the same for it. That is, until Fallen.\n\nThis book goes up there on a list of series favorites like the Wheel of Time's Lord of Chaos. Things happen and nothing will be the same. That commitment to step off the ledge is thrilling for the reader, especially 10 books in. There's only two more in the series as of this review and I'm really curious to see what happens next.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43670629
5:043699972	6:gr-43699972	3:Treasure Island	4:book review	60:Treasure Island	61:Marty Ross	62:2017	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2019-09-14	67:5/5	70:This is a brilliant dramatization with great acting and sound production. Treasure Island is a classic worthy of the title and this treatment did it justice. If you're looking for a good audio drama, here it is.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43699972
5:043747570	6:gr-43747570	3:Sunshine of Your Cult: Mission 5 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Sunshine of Your Cult: Mission 5 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2019	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-30	63:9781643550251	67:2/5	70:This was one of the weaker stories in the series so far. Esper without magic is kinda boring.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43747570
5:000043758	6:gr-43758	3:The Queen of the Damned (The Vampire Chronicles, #3)	4:book review	60:The Queen of the Damned (The Vampire Chronicles, #3)	61:Anne Rice	62:1997	64:Random House Publishing Group	68:read	69:2001-01-01	63:9780345419620	67:1/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43758
5:000043763	6:gr-43763	3:Interview with the Vampire (The Vampire Chronicles, #1)	4:book review	60:Interview with the Vampire (The Vampire Chronicles, #1)	61:Anne Rice	62:2004	64:Ballantine Books	68:read	69:1997-01-01	63:9780345476876	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43763
5:043807721	6:gr-43807721	3:Sovereign	4:book review	60:Sovereign	61:Jeff Hirsch	62:2019	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2019-02-14	67:1/5	70:I couldn't finish it. It was really weak.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43807721
5:000043808	6:gr-43808	3:Anne Rice's The Vampire Lestat: A Graphic Novel	4:book review	60:Anne Rice's The Vampire Lestat: A Graphic Novel	61:Faye Perozich	62:1991	64:Ballantine Books	68:read	69:2003-01-01	63:9780345373946	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43808
5:043811233	6:gr-43811233	3:Vervain and a Victim (The Witches of Wormwood Mysteries, #2)	4:book review	60:Vervain and a Victim (The Witches of Wormwood Mysteries, #2)	61:Silver Nord	62:2019	68:read	69:2021-06-29	67:3/5	70:There's something truly satisfying about these cozy witch mysteries. Perhaps it's the amateur vibe, the way they toss together monsters and borrowed fables with abandon, or the predictable characterization. They're easy to read and enjoy.\n\nI don't think this one was as strong as the first, but it carried me along nicely.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43811233
5:000043814	6:gr-43814	3:The Vampire Lestat (The Vampire Chronicles, #2)	4:book review	60:The Vampire Lestat (The Vampire Chronicles, #2)	61:Anne Rice	62:2004	64:Ballantine Books	68:read	69:1995-01-01	63:9780345476883	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43814
5:043819802	6:gr-43819802	3:Walk Like a Magician: Mission 6 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Walk Like a Magician: Mission 6 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2019	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-11	63:9781643550275	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43819802
5:043822024	6:gr-43822024	3:The Toll (Arc of a Scythe, #3)	4:book review	60:The Toll (Arc of a Scythe, #3)	61:Neal Shusterman	62:2019	64:Simon & Schuster Books for Young Readers	68:read	69:2020-01-28	63:9781481497060	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43822024
5:043822375	6:gr-43822375	3:The Ultimate RPG Gameplay Guide: Role-Play the Best Campaign Ever―No Matter the Game! (Ultimate Role Playing Game Series)	4:book review	60:The Ultimate RPG Gameplay Guide: Role-Play the Best Campaign Ever―No Matter the Game! (Ultimate Role Playing Game Series)	61:James D’Amato	62:2019	64:Adams Media	68:read	69:2022-03-18	63:9781507210932	67:4/5	70:This is a really solid book and I recommend it for anyone who wants to improve their tabletop role-playing gaming experience. There's just so many great bits in here!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43822375
5:000043889	6:gr-43889	3:Wizard's First Rule (Sword of Truth, #1)	4:book review	60:Wizard's First Rule (Sword of Truth, #1)	61:Terry Goodkind	62:2003	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:1996-01-01	63:9780765346520	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43889
5:043890637	6:gr-43890637	3:Jewel of the Endless Erg (Mage Errant, #2)	4:book review	60:Jewel of the Endless Erg (Mage Errant, #2)	61:John Bierce	62:2019	68:read	69:2021-08-30	67:3/5	70:The main characters, now well established, carry this story well. We get a new setting and increased world-building and leave more of the juvenile plot behind. Magical development scratches the same itch as a cultivation novel.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43890637
5:000043916	6:gr-43916	3:Magician (The Riftwar Saga, #1-2)	4:book review	60:Magician (The Riftwar Saga, #1-2)	61:Raymond E. Feist	62:2009	64:HarperCollins	68:read	69:2012-01-01	63:9780586217832	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/43916
5:000004407	6:gr-4407	3:American Gods (American Gods, #1)	4:book review	60:American Gods (American Gods, #1)	61:Neil Gaiman	62:2005	64:Headline Review	68:read	69:2012-06-04	67:1/5	70:It's sad to say, but this book just bored me. I usually like Neil Gaiman's stories, so don't read this as an attack on his talent or anything, but sometimes individual works just don't connect.\n\nIn this case, American Gods felt aimless, detached, and more than a little pointless. Not only did the big concepts fail to land, but the little stuff as well. It's one thing when you have a book like Neverwhere where a few of the characters are insanely quirky because it's balanced out by the "straight man". Unfortunately, Shadow is a terrible straight man. He doesn't question, he doesn't speak for the reader, he just follows along moving from story segment to story segment (note I don't call them plot points as most everything in here is useless to the overall plot.)\n\nNope, it just didn't work for me.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4407
5:044103363	6:gr-44103363	3:Hotel Caledonia: Mission 7 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Hotel Caledonia: Mission 7 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2019	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-16	63:9781643550329	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44103363
5:044148094	6:gr-44148094	3:Junk	4:book review	60:Junk	61:Les Bohem	62:2019	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2020-05-20	67:1/5	70:John Waters  couldn't save this. It's badly written.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44148094
5:000044186	6:gr-44186	3:The Monster at the End of this Book	4:book review	60:The Monster at the End of this Book	61:Jon Stone	62:2004	64:Golden Books	68:read	69:1984-01-01	63:9780375829130	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44186
5:000442122	6:gr-442122	3:Piers Anthony's Visual Guide to Xanth (Xanth)	4:book review	60:Piers Anthony's Visual Guide to Xanth (Xanth)	61:Piers Anthony	62:1989	64:Harper Perennial	68:read	69:2000-01-01	63:9780380757497	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/442122
5:000442128	6:gr-442128	3:Centaur Aisle (Xanth #4)	4:book review	60:Centaur Aisle (Xanth #4)	61:Piers Anthony	62:1987	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:1994-01-01	63:9780345352460	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/442128
5:044327636	6:gr-44327636	3:The First Step (A Thousand Li, #1)	4:book review	60:The First Step (A Thousand Li, #1)	61:Tao Wong	62:2019	64:Starlit Publishing	68:read	69:2021-04-25	63:9781989458006	67:4/5	70:This is my second series of novels in the cultivation genre. The Cradle books by Will Wight have more interesting fantasy elements and have a better sense of power scales from the start, but this series has much greater detail on the cultivation itself, the drama of the fights, and draws much from Chinese culture. I enjoy both and will continue the series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44327636
5:044652294	6:gr-44652294	3:Eye of the Pharaoh (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #8)	4:book review	60:Eye of the Pharaoh (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #8)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2019	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-16	63:9781643550459	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44652294
5:000044659	6:gr-44659	3:Pawn of Prophecy (The Belgariad, #1)	4:book review	60:Pawn of Prophecy (The Belgariad, #1)	61:David Eddings	62:2004	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2009-06-27	63:9780345468642	67:4/5	70:Some books don't hide the fact that they're going to be epic series. This is certainly one of those. The story barely gets started by the end of the first book, which isn't short by any means. The writing is fair with decent character development. I only had a few major pet peeves, the main one being the way the supplemental characters treat the main character.\n\nThe main boy is about 14 years old through the majority of the story, but the other characters treat him like a child of 8 or 9. He is physically washed by his aunt at one point, and he is constantly guarded and scorned for playing with sharp things.\n\nBeyond this, some of the characters seemed a little flat, which I attribute to new-writer syndrome. As this is only the first book in the series, I'm sure the depth of these characters will grow as the story does.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44659
5:000044660	6:gr-44660	3:The Belgariad Boxed Set: Pawn of Prophecy / Queen of Sorcery / Magician's Gambit / Castle of Wizardry / Enchanters' End Game (The Belgariad, #1-5)	4:book review	60:The Belgariad Boxed Set: Pawn of Prophecy / Queen of Sorcery / Magician's Gambit / Castle of Wizardry / Enchanters' End Game (The Belgariad, #1-5)	61:David Eddings	62:1986	64:Ballantine Books	68:read	69:2011-01-01	63:9780345340443	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44660
5:000044687	6:gr-44687	3:Enchanters' End Game (The Belgariad #5)	4:book review	60:Enchanters' End Game (The Belgariad #5)	61:David Eddings	62:1984	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2009-01-01	63:9780345300782	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44687
5:000044688	6:gr-44688	3:Magician's Gambit (The Belgariad #3)	4:book review	60:Magician's Gambit (The Belgariad #3)	61:David Eddings	62:1983	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2009-07-06	63:9780345335456	67:2/5	70:This was the weakest of the Belgariad books so far. Most of the book seemed like a rambling Dungeons and Dragons game filled with random encounters and new, made-up monsters described on the spot and forgotten about just as quickly. There was a smattering of character development, the introduction of a few new party members, and a short but satisfying showdown. \n\nI'm not really sure why the book was titled Magician's Gambit. There wasn't much of a gambit at all. Perhaps David Eddings should have named this book, "A Chorus Line of Gods and Random Monsters." At least then I'd know what I was going to run into.\n\nThe series still has life in it, though, and I'll press on. Here's to hoping book 4 is better than book 3.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44688
5:044765241	6:gr-44765241	3:Grave Descend	4:book review	60:Grave Descend	61:John Lange	62:2019	64:Open Road Media Mystery & Thriller	68:read	69:2023-01-10	67:2/5	70:The writing was fine but the story was, well, unnecessary. The main character figures out something is wrong before the action even begins and has ample time to turn everyone in to the police and walk away. Instead a rather nonsensical plot drags out which strains suspension of disbelief and strongly lacks sane character motivations.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44765241
5:044776980	6:gr-44776980	3:Agent Zero (Agent Zero, #1)	4:book review	60:Agent Zero (Agent Zero, #1)	61:Jack Mars	62:2019	68:read	69:2019-10-04	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44776980
5:044778083	6:gr-44778083	3:House of Earth and Blood (Crescent City, #1)	4:book review	60:House of Earth and Blood (Crescent City, #1)	61:Sarah J. Maas	62:2020	64:Bloomsbury Publishing	68:read	69:2022-05-28	63:9781635574043	67:1/5	70:Other reviews have done a far better job of thoroughly ripping this story apart, so I'll be brief: The characters are all flat. Too many "growl" reactions, everyone is too perfectly sexy and wants everyone else at all times no matter how many centuries old they might be. The investigation half of the story play-acts a mystery, but without bringing us along for the journey. Things just happen and then the characters snap at each other for another 50 pages. The ending is a mess. The world building is both too big and too small at the same time. It's a hodgepodge of stuff shoved into a story that can't decide what it wants to be.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/44778083
5:004502507	6:gr-4502507	3:The Last Olympian (Percy Jackson and the Olympians, #5)	4:book review	60:The Last Olympian (Percy Jackson and the Olympians, #5)	61:Rick Riordan	62:2009	68:read	69:2011-10-09	63:9780739380338	67:4/5	70:Stories based around prophecies are tough. Readers are pretty smart, so anything too simple and the mystery is ruined, but anything too obtuse and the ending seems cheap and contrived. It's a difficult thing to have a prophecy that in retrospect seems obvious yet isn't discovered along the way. I don't think Rick Riordan quite pulled it off, but it was close. The series ended very well and the aftermath was just long enough to settle everything that wanted settling. \n\nIn short, regarding the series as a whole, I'm really glad I took the time to read it. There's some really great characters, a lot of fun action, and plenty of silliness. It's a series that makes you want to go outside and have adventures while crying out battle cheers. \n\nIn fact...\n\nPEANUT BUTTER!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4502507
5:045028761	6:gr-45028761	3:Deathtrap (Mavericks, #1)	4:book review	60:Deathtrap (Mavericks, #1)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2019	68:read	69:2019-07-15	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45028761
5:045046734	6:gr-45046734	3:A Bond Undone (Legends of the Condor Heroes, #2)	4:book review	60:A Bond Undone (Legends of the Condor Heroes, #2)	61:Jin Yong	62:2020	64:St. Martin's Press	68:read	69:2023-10-30	63:9781250220684	67:5/5	70:I'm getting the hang of all the characters and names finally and the way things are coming together is great. Loved this one. Moving on!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45046734
5:045047384	6:gr-45047384	3:The House in the Cerulean Sea (The House in the Cerulean Sea, #1)	4:book review	60:The House in the Cerulean Sea (The House in the Cerulean Sea, #1)	61:T.J. Klune	62:2020	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2022-03-10	67:5/5	70:A charming, heart warming story. Give it a read and fall in love with all the characters, and bellhops!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45047384
5:000045101	6:gr-45101	3:The Mad Ship (Liveship Traders, #2)	4:book review	60:The Mad Ship (Liveship Traders, #2)	61:Robin Hobb	62:2008	64:Harper Voyager	68:read	63:9780006498865	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45101
5:000045102	6:gr-45102	3:Ship of Destiny (Liveship Traders, #3)	4:book review	60:Ship of Destiny (Liveship Traders, #3)	61:Robin Hobb	62:2001	64:Bantam Spectra	68:read	69:2002-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45102
5:000045112	6:gr-45112	3:Assassin's Quest (Farseer Trilogy, #3)	4:book review	60:Assassin's Quest (Farseer Trilogy, #3)	61:Robin Hobb	62:1998	64:Spectra	68:read	69:1995-01-01	63:9780553565690	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45112
5:045204131	6:gr-45204131	3:Pathfinder: Core Rulebook (Pathfinder, 2nd Edition)	4:book review	60:Pathfinder: Core Rulebook (Pathfinder, 2nd Edition)	61:Logan Bonner	62:2019	64:Paizo Inc.	68:read	69:2022-08-02	63:9781640781689	67:5/5	70:I love the rules changes. They've managed to simplify a lot of things, kill off areas that were black-holes for investment in PF1, and still kept a fantastic amount of customization. I'll be starting a new campaign for my crew in a few weeks and I'm so excited to see how these changes work in action.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45204131
5:000452304	6:gr-452304	3:Dracula (Signet Classics)	4:book review	60:Dracula (Signet Classics)	61:Bram Stoker	62:1986	64:Signet Classics	68:read	69:1994-01-01	63:9780451523372	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/452304
5:045367879	6:gr-45367879	3:Beautiful	4:book review	60:Beautiful	61:Juliet Marillier	62:2019	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2022-10-02	67:2/5	70:Juliet Marillier writes some excellent fairy tales. This one was solid enough but didn't really grab me. It was short enough to press on and finish, but nothing special.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45367879
5:045440171	6:gr-45440171	3:Black Crow, White Snow	4:book review	60:Black Crow, White Snow	61:Michael Livingston	62:2019	64:Audible Studio	68:read	69:2019-05-13	67:4/5	70:For once an Audible Original that delivered. Michael Livingston has done some very nice work in this short story, packing in a sense of grandeur to his worldbuilding and hinting at depth unrevealed. The characters were sharp and drove the action. He managed to sprinkle in layers of conflict including a crisis of conscience before a rather magnificent little payoff.\n\nMost of the criticism of this story in the comments on Goodreads are complaints that there's not enough of one thing or another. For its format I think it packed quite the punch. I hope that Mr. Livingston is expanding this world into something bigger for us in the future. I'd also like to see more of the Fair Isles and their war, and learn more of the people we've just gotten to know.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45440171
5:045447394	6:gr-45447394	3:Curriculum Vitae (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #8.1)	4:book review	60:Curriculum Vitae (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #8.1)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2019	68:read	69:2023-04-16	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/45447394
