5:049351872	6:gr-49351872	3:The First Stop (A Thousand Li, #2)	4:book review	60:The First Stop (A Thousand Li, #2)	61:Tao Wong	62:2019	64:Starlit Publishing	68:read	69:2021-08-20	63:9781989458105	67:3/5	70:Still no Cradle, but cultivation books are kinda neat.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49351872
5:049381341	6:gr-49381341	3:Peace Talks (The Dresden Files, #16)	4:book review	60:Peace Talks (The Dresden Files, #16)	61:Jim Butcher	62:2020	64:Ace	68:read	69:2021-02-02	63:9780451464415	67:3/5	70:It's been a while since I read a Dresden book. I needed to skim summaries of the last few to remember what's going on. Once things got rolling the familiar cadence returned and the large cast was fun to revisit. \n\nOne of the things I really like about these books is how the supporting characters grow and change over time. This book continued that somewhat. It also showed some tough decision making scenes for Harry. That's the bread & butter. There's also the familiar with edges, an underlying sense of wish fulfillment from the author, over-sexualized women, and that feeling you get when someone tells you a story about their witty comebacks that you suspect were thought up much later in the shower.\n\nThis book is a set up for the next one. It shouldn't be it's own book at all. I'm not sure if that was an action by the publisher or author scared of a big page count. I'll start on the next one right away. I'm eager to see how this turns out as we enter act 2.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49381341
5:049416459	6:gr-49416459	3:The Half-Life of Marie Curie	4:book review	60:The Half-Life of Marie Curie	61:Lauren Gunderson	62:2019	64:Audible	68:read	69:2019-12-31	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49416459
5:049469698	6:gr-49469698	3:Rando Splicer (The Spiral Wars, #6)	4:book review	60:Rando Splicer (The Spiral Wars, #6)	61:Joel Shepherd	62:2019	68:read	69:2021-11-05	67:4/5	70:There's some brutal stuff in this one, but what I liked most was the major scenery changes. We got dusty for a bit. Deserts and jungles, train battles and seiges. The great story arc inches forward and the stakes keep raising. This is a really solid series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49469698
5:000049540	6:gr-49540	3:Les Liaisons dangereuses	4:book review	60:Les Liaisons dangereuses	61:Pierre Choderlos de Laclos	62:1999	64:Oxford University Press	68:read	69:2017-09-16	63:9780192838674	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/49540
5:004961957	6:gr-4961957	3:Furies of Calderon (The Codex Alera, #1)	4:book review	60:Furies of Calderon (The Codex Alera, #1)	61:Jim Butcher	62:2009	64:Orbit	68:read	69:2022-02-10	63:9781841497440	67:1/5	70:DNF. There was a gross amount of abuse, and a gross amount of lazy writing. It became a slog and I gave up about 60% of the way	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4961957
5:000004980	6:gr-4980	3:Breakfast of Champions	4:book review	60:Breakfast of Champions	61:Kurt Vonnegut Jr.	62:1999	64:Dell Publishing	68:read	69:2022-09-16	63:9780385334204	67:2/5	70:I can see why it's a successful book and I can understand why people would have eaten it up in the same way Robert Crumb captured minds. Despite this I felt a great distance from it. The humor and absurdities didn't break the shell of society to reveal cracks of honest truth, they felt like a cartoonist's caricature work. The themes were explored, but without heart.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/4980
