5:053020704	6:gr-53020704	3:CAPTAIN MARVEL VS. ROGUE	4:book review	60:CAPTAIN MARVEL VS. ROGUE	61:Chris Claremont	62:2021	64:Marvel Universe	68:read	69:2021-12-25	63:9781302926519	67:4/5	70:I love the showdowns between these two. I'm glad to see it all captured in one big volume.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53020704
5:053179797	6:gr-53179797	3:Critical Mass (Expeditionary Force, #10)	4:book review	60:Critical Mass (Expeditionary Force, #10)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2020	68:read	69:2020-10-31	67:5/5	70:Best book of the series so far. What an ending!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53179797
5:053205794	6:gr-53205794	3:The Last Watch (The Divide, #1)	4:book review	60:The Last Watch (The Divide, #1)	61:J.S. Dewes	62:2021	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2022-09-04	63:9781250236340	67:3/5	70:This started really strong with vibrant characters and world-building. The second half of the story started to drag, though. It invested more in character development than action, which is a fair choice, but it lost a lot of momentum in doing so. There's a lot left open at the end that promises at an interesting series. I'll probably get around to them eventually.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53205794
5:053205854	6:gr-53205854	3:Fugitive Telemetry (The Murderbot Diaries, #6)	4:book review	60:Fugitive Telemetry (The Murderbot Diaries, #6)	61:Martha Wells	62:2021	64:Tor.com	68:read	69:2021-07-25	63:9781250765376	67:4/5	70:Murderbot has settled into its new life on Preservation Station. This sixth book has also settled nicely into the setting. There's action, adventure, and a nice mystery. It's a solid continuation of the series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53205854
5:000005326	6:gr-5326	3:A Christmas Carol	4:book review	60:A Christmas Carol	61:Charles Dickens	62:1999	64:Bethany House Publishers	68:read	69:1988-01-01	63:9781561797462	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5326
5:053300479	6:gr-53300479	3:How to Defeat a Demon King in Ten Easy Steps	4:book review	60:How to Defeat a Demon King in Ten Easy Steps	61:Andrew Rowe	62:2020	64:Audible Original	68:read	69:2020-05-12	67:3/5	70:This was an Audible freebie. It was also a sneaky litrpg, a genre I really don't care for. Still, it was funny and had plenty of Zelda references which was nice. Voice acting was good too.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53300479
5:053319151	6:gr-53319151	3:Brushfire (Expeditionary Force, #11)	4:book review	60:Brushfire (Expeditionary Force, #11)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2020	64:Independently published	68:read	69:2021-01-12	63:9798580899206	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53319151
5:053322519	6:gr-53322519	3:No More Mr. Nice Girl: Mission 10	4:book review	60:No More Mr. Nice Girl: Mission 10	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-20	63:9781643550916	67:3/5	70:Oh dear... that's a turn	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53322519
5:053406893	6:gr-53406893	3:The Sandman: Act I	4:book review	60:The Sandman: Act I	61:Dirk Maggs	62:2020	64:Audible Originals	68:read	69:2021-02-09	67:2/5	70:The graphic novel is the way to go. This was too abridged, the music too invasive, and the voice acting can't carry the weight of the missing visuals.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53406893
5:053438195	6:gr-53438195	3:The Witch's Heart	4:book review	60:The Witch's Heart	61:Genevieve Gornichec	62:2021	64:Ace	68:read	69:2022-04-16	63:9780593099940	66:friend-recommended	67:3/5	70:This took me a really long time to finish. The slow pacing led me to take breaks throughout, inserting other audiobooks in between. The story is engaging and familiar, but the deep characterization and introspection carry it well, even in long stretches without any action or plot movement.\n\nThe feel reminds me of Song of Achilles but it is even more brought away from scene work in the narrative. As I mentioned, the pacing is incredibly slow as a result, but the writing is rich without being verbose, beautiful without being flowery, and accessible despite being about gods and giants.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53438195
5:000534415	6:gr-534415	3:Dragons of Summer Flame (Dragonlance: The Second Generation, #2)	4:book review	60:Dragons of Summer Flame (Dragonlance: The Second Generation, #2)	61:Margaret Weis	62:1995	64:TSR, Inc.	68:read	69:1995-01-01	63:9780786901890	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/534415
5:000534420	6:gr-534420	3:Dragons of a Lost Star (Dragonlance: The War of Souls, #2)	4:book review	60:Dragons of a Lost Star (Dragonlance: The War of Souls, #2)	61:Margaret Weis	62:2001	64:Wizards of the Coast	68:read	69:1999-01-01	63:9780786918171	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/534420
5:053451709	6:gr-53451709	3:Magic's Little Helper (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #11)	4:book review	60:Magic's Little Helper (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #11)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-20	63:9781643550930	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53451709
5:053451737	6:gr-53451737	3:Mortanian Rhapsody: Mission 12 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #12)	4:book review	60:Mortanian Rhapsody: Mission 12 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #12)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-24	63:9781643550961	67:3/5	70:I feel like this series keeps missing the mark. I have glimmers of stuff I like, and then it goes in weird directions. It's great when we touch back on old crew from the Mobius and get some of that magic back, but it's rare.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53451737
5:053462468	6:gr-53462468	3:Once More Upon a Time	4:book review	60:Once More Upon a Time	61:Roshani Chokshi	62:2020	64:Audible	68:read	69:2020-06-24	67:1/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53462468
5:053485742	6:gr-53485742	3:Our Little Secret (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #12.5)	4:book review	60:Our Little Secret (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #12.5)	61:J.S. Morin	68:read	69:2023-04-24	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53485742
5:000005358	6:gr-5358	3:The Firm	4:book review	60:The Firm	61:Robin Waterfield	62:2000	64:Addison Wesley Publishing Company	68:read	69:1997-01-01	63:9780582418271	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5358
5:000000536	6:gr-536	3:The Lovely Bones	4:book review	60:The Lovely Bones	61:Alice Sebold	62:2006	64:Random House	68:read	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/536
5:000053732	6:gr-53732	3:Dune	4:book review	60:Dune	61:Frank Herbert	62:1990	64:Ace/Berkley Books	68:read	69:2008-01-01	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53732
5:053831501	6:gr-53831501	3:Success Leaves Traces: An Incredible Method to Change Your Life By Embracing Little Known Mental Strategies Designed to Create The Life You Deserve	4:book review	60:Success Leaves Traces: An Incredible Method to Change Your Life By Embracing Little Known Mental Strategies Designed to Create The Life You Deserve	61:Armand Morin	62:2020	64:Morgan James Publishing	68:read	69:2020-09-26	67:5/5	70:Armand's method is one of those things that makes you nod along as you read it thinking to yourself, "well if course! That's obvious!" Except it wasn't obvious five minutes ago. Through a combination of systematic processes and a folksy walk down memory lane he lays bare his own path to success. The stumbling blocks make sense and help explain the next part of a bigger vision in such an organic way that what seems at first like a narrative following his train of thoughts was in actuality a micro-example of the entire system itself.\n\nArmand doesn't try to impress with high science or eloquent prose. He stay true to his own rules and presents himself authentically, and the sale is stronger for it.\n\nIf you're in need of motivation and a plan for the next step in your life this wouldn't be a bad read. It's quick and applicable to far more than business.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/53831501
5:000540020	6:gr-540020	3:The Day of the Jackal	4:book review	60:The Day of the Jackal	61:Frederick Forsyth	62:1979	64:Bantam	68:read	69:2000-01-01	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/540020
5:054241214	6:gr-54241214	3:Warping Minds & Other Misdemeanors (The Guild Codex: Warped, #1)	4:book review	60:Warping Minds & Other Misdemeanors (The Guild Codex: Warped, #1)	61:Annette Marie	62:2020	68:read	69:2022-08-23	67:1/5	70:The writing isn't very strong. The characters are shallow and the movie buff quirk feels less a character aspect than a trick to hide a lack of personality. My worst complaint is for the audiobook reader, however. Just atrocious work. His women's voices are not just bad but unfitting to their characters. Everyone else is a caricature.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54241214
5:054245639	6:gr-54245639	3:Spellmaker (Spellbreaker Duology, #2)	4:book review	60:Spellmaker (Spellbreaker Duology, #2)	61:Charlie N. Holmberg	62:2021	64:47North	68:read	69:2021-08-13	63:9781542022583	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54245639
5:000543330	6:gr-543330	3:The Renegades of Pern (Pern, #10)	4:book review	60:The Renegades of Pern (Pern, #10)	61:Anne McCaffrey	62:1990	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:1994-01-01	63:9780345369338	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/543330
5:054369251	6:gr-54369251	3:A Wizard’s Guide to Defensive Baking	4:book review	60:A Wizard’s Guide to Defensive Baking	61:T. Kingfisher	62:2020	64:Argyll Productions	68:read	69:2022-05-20	63:9781614505242	67:3/5	70:This was a fun adventure with lots of baking adventures, incompetent adults, high stakes placed on teens, and quirky characters. It's quick and light with a few tense scenes and easy pacing.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54369251
5:054425910	6:gr-54425910	3:The Girls Are Back In Town: Mission 13 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:The Girls Are Back In Town: Mission 13 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-24	63:9781643551067	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54425910
5:054493401	6:gr-54493401	3:Project Hail Mary	4:book review	60:Project Hail Mary	61:Andy Weir	62:2021	64:Ballantine Books	68:read	69:2021-07-18	63:9780593135204	67:5/5	70:In this work Andy Weir returns to his excellent recipe from The Martian moreso than his experiements in Artemis. The technique pays off and we're left with another thrill-packed science-triumph. The story offers plenty of adversity and even some emotional moments of despair, but a calm head and ingenuity can accomplish miracles.\n\nI would highly recommend picking this up on audiobook over paper. To explain why is a spoiler, so just take my word for it.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54493401
5:054511226	6:gr-54511226	3:Dawnshard (The Stormlight Archive, #3.5)	4:book review	60:Dawnshard (The Stormlight Archive, #3.5)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2020	64:Dragonsteel Entertainment	68:read	69:2022-10-02	63:193857026X	67:5/5	70:I'm going to reread this series as I prepare for the next book. It's too big and complex to continue after these long breaks. To that end, Dawnshard was an excellent primer for the reread. It brought me back into the world and reminded me of all the excellent things that are happening.\n\nIts own story was quite good too. The characters were clearly defined with their own struggles. Sanderson's depiction of disablility and the way it influenced action and internal struggle was wonderful. I understand he had quite a team to consult with on those aspects and it really showed. The character journey was the strongest force in the novella, overshadowing the plot developments and ending revelations. This is particularly impressive since there were quite a few new developments in the cosmere worldbuilding here.\n\nIf you're reading the Stormlight Archive, don't skip these novellas. They're as worthy as the main books.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54511226
5:054615879	6:gr-54615879	3:The Original	4:book review	60:The Original	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2020	64:Recorded Books	68:read	69:2022-12-22	67:2/5	70:Not bad, but left a lot of good possibilities on the table. It didn't feel as well thought through as Sanderson's typical works.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54615879
5:054649023	6:gr-54649023	3:Pathfinder Adventure Path: Devil at the Dreaming Palace (Agents of Edgewatch 1 of 6) (P2)	4:book review	60:Pathfinder Adventure Path: Devil at the Dreaming Palace (Agents of Edgewatch 1 of 6) (P2)	61:James L. Sutter	62:2020	64:Paizo Publishing	68:read	69:2022-09-02	63:9781640782532	67:4/5	70:Love it. There's a ton of good content here. Great variety of encounters. Lots of options to give players freedom. The theme is flexible if you have issues with it, and Paizo put out some helpful toolbox stuff to get around problem areas.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54649023
5:000546650	6:gr-546650	3:Gutenberg: How One Man Remade the World with Words	4:book review	60:Gutenberg: How One Man Remade the World with Words	61:John Man	62:2002	64:John Wiley & Sons	68:read	69:2008-01-01	63:9780471218234	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/546650
5:000005470	6:gr-5470	3:1984	4:book review	60:1984	61:George Orwell	62:1950	64:New American Library	68:read	69:1996-01-01	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5470
5:054706020	6:gr-54706020	3:Stuck in the Astral with You: Mission 14 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Stuck in the Astral with You: Mission 14 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-24	63:9781643551098	67:2/5	70:I feel like I slept through this one.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/54706020
5:055001433	6:gr-55001433	3:Lair of the Dog: Mission 15 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Lair of the Dog: Mission 15 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-24	63:9781643551128	67:2/5	70:There were some fun moments here, but whether it was too many plot lines, or just poor planning, we ended up spending the majority of the book with the wrong characters. If they shunted everyone else aside and gave Kubu the full focus in this book I think we'd have been better off. There was so much to explore in his character and the Poltid culture that just didn't happen. The resolution was telegraphed from the start and felt rushed even so. There was a nice glimmer of time with Tanny and Wesley where we got a bit more of his character, but I don't think it was worth all the time and attention we spent with them. Action didn't move as a result and nothing felt at stake. Esper's time away these last two books could have been shown in a couple paragraphs after meeting back up. There was nothing in any of that activity either.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55001433
5:000055030	6:gr-55030	3:Cosmos	4:book review	60:Cosmos	61:Carl Sagan	62:2002	64:Random House	68:read	69:2020-08-21	63:9780375508325	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55030
5:055133107	6:gr-55133107	3:Empathy for the Devil: Mission 16 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	4:book review	60:Empathy for the Devil: Mission 16 (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2020	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-04-26	63:9781643551159	67:2/5	70:Well, that wraps it up. All the main plot lines are closed and resolution happening. I didn't love it, but characters did grow and change and things progressed. It's nice knowing where all our main heroes have ended up. Still, meh. The Mobius stories were much stronger.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55133107
5:055187745	6:gr-55187745	3:The Dragon Squisher	4:book review	60:The Dragon Squisher	61:Scott McCormick	62:2020	68:read	69:2020-09-17	67:1/5	70:This is neither a kid's book nor entertaining enough for adults. It's aimless.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55187745
5:055259808	6:gr-55259808	3:Wayward Galaxy (Wayward Galaxy, #1)	4:book review	60:Wayward Galaxy (Wayward Galaxy, #1)	61:Jason Anspach	62:2020	64:Variant Publications	68:read	69:2022-04-13	67:1/5	70:DNF. Despite excellent narration from R.C. Bray, the story was just not there. It leaned into a good-guy / bad-guy vibe using an awkward political divide that harkens back to the 70s and 80s and which doesn't work anymore. Characters had no dimension to them and the humor was anachronistic.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55259808
5:055291869	6:gr-55291869	3:Murder by Other Means (The Dispatcher, #2)	4:book review	60:Murder by Other Means (The Dispatcher, #2)	61:John Scalzi	62:2020	64:Audible Originals	68:read	69:2020-10-14	67:4/5	70:Nice and short with solid narration. There was enough mystery to keep me guessing and the ending wrapped up nicely too.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55291869
5:055354918	6:gr-55354918	3:The Last Graduate (The Scholomance, #2)	4:book review	60:The Last Graduate (The Scholomance, #2)	61:Naomi Novik	62:2021	64:Del Rey Books	68:read	63:9780593128879	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55354918
5:000055399	6:gr-55399	3:Gardens of the Moon (Malazan Book of the Fallen, #1)	4:book review	60:Gardens of the Moon (Malazan Book of the Fallen, #1)	61:Steven Erikson	62:2005	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2011-05-26	63:9780765348784	67:3/5	70:1) Definitely dense, but with a lot of action. I think Erickson did a fine job introducing us to his world without too much exposition. Granted, it was a little confusing in parts, but by the time things really came to a head, I had it pretty well sorted out.\n\n2) His characters are fairly strong, which is good since there are so many.  \n\n3) The balance of the "epic" scale was a little skewed. It was really hard to tell which God or God-like being was going to suddenly be more powerful. In this it reminded me a bit of Dragonball Z, with the characters suddenly powering up and showing new hidden strength, but with Malazan, it was harder to tell which was actually more powerful. Perhaps further reading will reveal that balance a bit more.\n\n4) Meh... I'm bored of reviewing. :)	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55399
5:000055401	6:gr-55401	3:Deadhouse Gates (Malazan Book of the Fallen, #2)	4:book review	60:Deadhouse Gates (Malazan Book of the Fallen, #2)	61:Steven Erikson	62:2005	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2011-07-31	63:9780765310026	67:4/5	70:I think the place these books succeed is at the very end. For the majority of the read I find myself confused, bored, and really not connected to the characters at all. Then Steven Erikson slaps me around with a solid ending with great pacing and a series of cliffhangers that makes me want to go through it all again. I feel like an abused lover.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55401
5:055419950	6:gr-55419950	3:The Second Expedition (A Thousand Li, #4)	4:book review	60:The Second Expedition (A Thousand Li, #4)	61:Tao Wong	62:2020	64:Starlit Publishing	68:read	69:2022-05-15	63:9781989994092	67:4/5	70:This series is growing on me. There's a calmeness to this slow cultivation even in the midst of battles. It's cozy.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55419950
5:055559887	6:gr-55559887	3:The Last Graduate (The Scholomance, #2)	4:book review	60:The Last Graduate (The Scholomance, #2)	61:Naomi Novik	62:2021	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2021-10-12	63:9780593128862	67:4/5	70:A really solid follow-up but what a sudden ending! Gah! I need another chapter or two, please.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55559887
5:055595995	6:gr-55595995	3:Bloodline (Cradle, #9)	4:book review	60:Bloodline (Cradle, #9)	61:Will Wight	62:2021	64:Hidden Gnome Publishing	68:read	69:2021-04-18	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55595995
5:055849312	6:gr-55849312	3:Qalea Drop (The Spiral Wars, #7)	4:book review	60:Qalea Drop (The Spiral Wars, #7)	61:Joel Shepherd	62:2020	64:Joel Shepherd	68:read	69:2021-11-24	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55849312
5:055858638	6:gr-55858638	3:The Golden Enclaves (The Scholomance, #3)	4:book review	60:The Golden Enclaves (The Scholomance, #3)	61:Naomi Novik	62:2022	64:Del Rey Books	68:read	69:2022-10-19	63:9780593158364	67:3/5	70:This was a decent enough conclusion to the trilogy, but not as tight as the earlier books. Things bogged down in the middle and the ending was just a little too rosy.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55858638
5:055870343	6:gr-55870343	3:Kubu’s First Date (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #16.5)	4:book review	60:Kubu’s First Date (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire, #16.5)	61:J.S. Morin	68:read	69:2023-04-27	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/55870343
5:000559336	6:gr-559336	3:The Book of Old Ships: From Egyptian Galleys to Clipper Ships	4:book review	60:The Book of Old Ships: From Egyptian Galleys to Clipper Ships	61:Henry B. Culver	62:1992	64:Dover Publications	68:read	69:2019-06-28	63:9780486273327	67:4/5	70:I'm finished as much as one can be with a reference book. This has it all!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/559336
5:056032923	6:gr-56032923	3:Drinking Heavy Water: a Montague Portal novel	4:book review	60:Drinking Heavy Water: a Montague Portal novel	61:Michael Warren Lucas	62:2020	68:read	69:2023-01-10	67:5/5	70:Eek! I love this series. The infinite universes make fabulous settings for the action to play out, and of course every bad thing that can happen will happen. That's expected from the premise and would be fun enough on its own. What's makes this so good, though, is the depth of humanity in the main character. Her motivations and feelings are crystal clear, as are her struggles with the trauma from the earlier stories. When she smiles with joy so too so I. When she feels the despair counting down her remaining breaths, I'm holding my own.\n\nThese are fabulous stories and masterfully written. I recommend them to everyone whose eyes open wide at the thought of traveling to another universe.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56032923
5:000560441	6:gr-560441	3:Spa Bodywork: A Guide For Massage Therapists	4:book review	60:Spa Bodywork: A Guide For Massage Therapists	61:Anne     Williams	62:2006	64:Lippincott Williams & Wilkins	68:read	69:2017-01-15	63:9780781755788	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/560441
5:000561456	6:gr-561456	3:The Titan's Curse (Percy Jackson and the Olympians, #3)	4:book review	60:The Titan's Curse (Percy Jackson and the Olympians, #3)	61:Rick Riordan	62:2007	64:Puffin Books	68:read	69:2011-10-06	63:9780141382890	67:3/5	70:I don't think this one was nearly as engaging as the last adventure, but it was still a good read. There were enough hints of things to come that I'm still interested in going forward.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/561456
5:056151914	6:gr-56151914	3:Bones of the Past (Villains' Code, #2)	4:book review	60:Bones of the Past (Villains' Code, #2)	61:Drew  Hayes	62:2020	68:read	69:2021-05-28	67:5/5	70:This is a clear improvement over the first book in the series, which was already quite good. Here the author took his time to dive deeper into the inner motivations of the heroes and villains to great effect. The action was still there to keep it all moving forward. Multiple interwoven plots and character goals drove a tight story. This series will be one to follow.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56151914
5:005617966	6:gr-5617966	3:A Guide to the Good Life: The Ancient Art of Stoic Joy	4:book review	60:A Guide to the Good Life: The Ancient Art of Stoic Joy	61:William B. Irvine	62:2009	64:Oxford University Press	68:read	69:2016-01-03	63:9780195374612	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5617966
5:056208572	6:gr-56208572	3:Pinball Wizardry (Black Ocean, #8.5)	4:book review	60:Pinball Wizardry (Black Ocean, #8.5)	61:J.S. Morin	62:2015	64:Magical Scrivener Press	68:read	69:2023-03-07	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56208572
5:056222485	6:gr-56222485	3:Achieving Harmony (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire #16.8)	4:book review	60:Achieving Harmony (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire #16.8)	61:J.S. Morin	68:read	69:2023-04-27	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56222485
5:056222507	6:gr-56222507	3:Mercenary Intentions (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire #0.5)	4:book review	60:Mercenary Intentions (Black Ocean: Mercy for Hire #0.5)	61:J.S. Morin	68:read	69:2023-04-27	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56222507
5:056358066	6:gr-56358066	3:Risen (Alex Verus, #12)	4:book review	60:Risen (Alex Verus, #12)	61:Benedict Jacka	62:2021	64:Ace Books	68:read	69:2022-08-16	67:5/5	70:An excellent and bloody conclusion to the series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56358066
5:056392536	6:gr-56392536	3:Professor Spindlebrock's Little Blue Book of Traveling Spells	4:book review	60:Professor Spindlebrock's Little Blue Book of Traveling Spells	61:Joseph Lyman	62:2020	64:Pinpoint Management LLC	68:read	69:2021-05-30	67:3/5	70:This short one took me a bit longer than normal, probably because I am an acquaintence of the author and I wanted to give it some extra attention and leeway where I might otherwise be critical. My review will be brief, regardless.\n\nThere's much good to be said about Professor Spindlebrock's Little Blue Book of Traveling Spells. The world-building, characterizations, and even the novelty of magic itself make this quirky and fun. I appreciated the subtlty and realism of the magical effects along with the practicality of the little volume that is a book within a book. The story was well thought out and had me wanting to know what happens next.\n\nThe part I struggled with and which I suspect many will find difficult is the amount of "telling" instead of "showing". The entire introduction of the book, really, was an info-dump in the telling style. While we have vingettes of a sort that dive into a particular scene everything still felt colored by that default mode. If I were an editor working with Mr. Lyman on this book I would tell him with thrilled excitement that he has an amazing outline with key scenes flushed out. He should now go and expand out those parts that he's brushing over to bring the whole thing to life that much more. In fact, in doing so I bet he could fit in a B and C plotline that winds through the story as well, giving depth to an otherwise straight-forward affair.\n\nI'm excited to see what he writes next.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56392536
5:056481094	6:gr-56481094	3:Rise of the Witch (The Yaga's Riders, #1)	4:book review	60:Rise of the Witch (The Yaga's Riders, #1)	61:C. Rochelle	62:2021	68:read	69:2022-10-04	67:1/5	70:The writing is high school quality: too formal, verbose, and with far too many adjectives shoved where they aren't needed. The accent on the lady narrator is atrocious. DNF.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56481094
5:000565256	6:gr-565256	3:An Anthology of Christian Mysticism (Pueblo Books)	4:book review	60:An Anthology of Christian Mysticism (Pueblo Books)	61:Harvey D. Egan	62:1991	64:Liturgical Press	68:read	69:2010-12-26	63:9780814660126	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/565256
5:000056842	6:gr-56842	3:Fatherland	4:book review	60:Fatherland	61:Robert   Harris	62:1992	64:Harper Paperbacks	68:read	69:2018-11-04	63:9780061006623	67:2/5	70:The world is already too dark. I need to re-read this when life is beautiful	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56842
5:056864154	6:gr-56864154	3:Rule of Cool	4:book review	60:Rule of Cool	61:Matthew Siege	62:2021	68:read	69:2021-02-27	67:2/5	70:Felicia Day did an excellent job reading this one. It is, frankly, the only reason I bought the book and the only reason I stuck with it. I am not a LitRPG fan and this book is deep into that style. Be prepared to have stats and rolls read out to you.\n\nIt was nice to be on the other side of the fence from the typical heroes, but I think the LitRPG books from the POV of the dungeons are better at it than this one. The humor was childish and eye-roll-worthy. Nothing groundbreaking.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/56864154
5:057102038	6:gr-57102038	3:Reincarnation (Threads of Fate, #1)	4:book review	60:Reincarnation (Threads of Fate, #1)	61:Michael  Head	62:2021	64:Mountaindale Press	68:read	69:2022-09-16	67:2/5	70:Here we have a cultivation series showing what would happen if the main character had cheat codes. It's Mary Sue through and through, but it doesn't pretend to be otherwise. The adventure is pretty fun regardless and I picked up the next two books for next to nothing in a sale so I'll keep going.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57102038
5:057113375	6:gr-57113375	3:Winter Trials (Threads of Fate, #2)	4:book review	60:Winter Trials (Threads of Fate, #2)	61:Michael  Head	62:2021	64:Mountaindale Press	68:read	69:2022-09-18	67:1/5	70:My misgivings about book one were confirmed here and in greater display. The excuse of backstory bought the series summer leeway with wish fulfillment badass mcgoo but the character is irredeemable. His choices mature no sense even internally. His actions win the day without risk and the rewards are meaningless. I could rant more (and I did to my wife) but all this is to say... DNF.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57113375
5:057128924	6:gr-57128924	3:The Alpha Protocol (Alpha Protocol, #1)	4:book review	60:The Alpha Protocol (Alpha Protocol, #1)	61:Duncan M. Hamilton	62:2021	68:read	69:2022-01-01	67:1/5	70:DNF.\n\nThe audiobook narrator is criminally bad. The accents are atrocious and over-the-top. The choice of accents for any given character seem random and unaligned with the descriptions of their actions and personalities. Really I could go on and on, but yeah, don't get the audiobook.\n\nAs for the story itself, I gave it far more effort than it deserved thinking my frustrations were due solely to the narration. It turns out the plot is weak too. The sci-fi terminology is ripped from a dozen other sources, which is rather confusing, actually. The new ideas presented aren't new. The actions of our protagonist are...weak. It didn't marry up with the description of who the character was supposed to be or how he was trained.\n\nActually, all the characters were weak. Almost all were paper thin. There's no notable female presence in the story at all.\n\nCannot recommend.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57128924
5:000571740	6:gr-571740	3:The Reader's Companion to Alaska	4:book review	60:The Reader's Companion to Alaska	61:Alan Ryan	62:1997	64:Mariner Books	68:read	69:2006-01-01	63:9780156003681	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/571740
5:000005720	6:gr-5720	3:Rainbow Six (John Clark, #2; Jack Ryan Universe, #10)	4:book review	60:Rainbow Six (John Clark, #2; Jack Ryan Universe, #10)	61:Tom Clancy	62:1999	64:Berkley Books	68:read	69:1999-01-01	63:9780425170342	67:2/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5720
5:057342343	6:gr-57342343	3:Vicarious	4:book review	60:Vicarious	61:Rhett C. Bruno	62:2021	64:Aethon Books	68:read	69:2021-09-02	67:2/5	70:I struggled with the second half of this. The pacing was frustrating and some of the character decisions made little sense or felt forced by plot more than their own personalities. Even so, it ended in an interesting way that I enjoyed.\n\nWil Wheaton's audio narration was a big help. I don't think I'd have stuck with it the whole way without that.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57342343
5:000574848	6:gr-574848	3:Chris-In-The-Morning: Love, Life, and the Whole Karmic Enchilada	4:book review	60:Chris-In-The-Morning: Love, Life, and the Whole Karmic Enchilada	61:Louis Chunovic	62:1993	64:Contemporary Books	68:read	69:2005-01-01	63:9780809237623	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/574848
5:057571215	6:gr-57571215	3:Cytonic (Skyward, #3)	4:book review	60:Cytonic (Skyward, #3)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2021	64:Delacorte Press	68:read	69:2021-12-27	63:9780399555855	67:1/5	70:DNF.\n\nI was just completely bored with this story right from the start. It's incredible since I was really into the first two in the series and I even pre-ordered this with the expectations of wrapping up a really good series. The choice to take the action into the Nowhere and thus decoupled from the realities of the settings so far erased my connection to those settings. The nonsensical nature of these fragments and the way they shuttled past one after another made me uninterested in developing any connections to what was going on. The new character in that setting was likewise swept up in the wave of irrelevance. I don't think I made it even 25% of the way into the book before I realized I had no idea what was going on because I'd stopped paying attention.\n\nThis is the first utter failure of a Sanderson book I've run into since Elantris. I hope it's a one-off.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57571215
5:057611982	6:gr-57611982	3:Beware of Chicken 2	4:book review	60:Beware of Chicken 2	61:CasualFarmer	62:2023	68:read	69:2023-04-03	67:4/5	70:More light-hearted fun	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57611982
5:057632292	6:gr-57632292	3:Noor	4:book review	60:Noor	61:Nnedi Okorafor	62:2021	64:DAW	68:read	69:2022-09-20	63:9780756416096	67:4/5	70:There's a lot packed into this short novel. It manages to blend a positivistic African Futurism\nwith the gritty realities of prejudice, monopoly, and corruption. Really well done.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57632292
5:057640065	6:gr-57640065	3:Reaper (Cradle, #10)	4:book review	60:Reaper (Cradle, #10)	61:Will Wight	62:2021	64:Hidden Gnome Publishing	68:read	69:2021-12-10	67:3/5	70:The main story progression is still working but it's becoming increasingly difficult to follow the action clearly as battles take on more and more epic scopes.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57640065
5:057662892	6:gr-57662892	3:Breakaway (Expeditionary Force, #12)	4:book review	60:Breakaway (Expeditionary Force, #12)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2021	68:read	69:2021-06-29	67:5/5	70:A wild ride as always	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57662892
5:057795441	6:gr-57795441	3:The Squire	4:book review	60:The Squire	61:Duncan M. Hamilton	62:2021	64:Independently Published	68:read	69:2021-06-12	63:9798731336253	67:4/5	70:I really enjoyed the Wolf of the North series and this picks up in that world again with some familiar names, places, and creatures, but a whole new story to tell. The characters are vibrant and keep things engaging even when we dip into trope. I can't wait for book two.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57795441
5:057824703	6:gr-57824703	3:The Second Sect (A Thousand Li #5)	4:book review	60:The Second Sect (A Thousand Li #5)	61:Tao Wong	62:2021	64:Starlit Publishing	68:read	69:2022-07-07	63:9781989994788	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57824703
5:000057854	6:gr-57854	3:Tao Te Ching	4:book review	60:Tao Te Ching	61:Lao Tzu	62:1997	64:Vintage/Random House (NY)	68:read	69:2012-12-04	63:9780679776192	67:5/5	70:Another reread and it's as good as ever.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57854
5:057951331	6:gr-57951331	3:The Jade Setter of Janloon (The Green Bone Saga, #0.5)	4:book review	60:The Jade Setter of Janloon (The Green Bone Saga, #0.5)	61:Fonda Lee	62:2022	64:Subterranean Press	68:read	69:2023-06-27	63:9781645240624	67:3/5	70:A fun side adventure dipping back into familiar characters and seeing. The stakes were smaller but enjoyable	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/57951331
5:000058107	6:gr-58107	3:Bobby Fischer Teaches Chess	4:book review	60:Bobby Fischer Teaches Chess	61:Bobby Fischer	62:1982	64:Bantam	68:read	69:2000-01-01	63:9780553263152	66:chess	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58107
5:058134022	6:gr-58134022	3:Aidan Redding Against the Universes: a Montague Portal omnibus	4:book review	60:Aidan Redding Against the Universes: a Montague Portal omnibus	61:Michael Warren Lucas	62:2021	68:read	69:2023-01-11	67:5/5	70:I loved the three main books so much and reviewed each individually. The two bonus short stories were cool glimpses into the portal worlds as well. I really can't wait for more adventures in the series.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58134022
5:058306874	6:gr-58306874	3:Lakesedge (World at the Lake's Edge, #1)	4:book review	60:Lakesedge (World at the Lake's Edge, #1)	61:Lyndall Clipstone	62:2021	64:Henry Holt and Co.	68:read	69:2021-12-17	66:friend-recommended	67:2/5	70:Lakesedge was a really interesting debut novel from Lyndall Clipstone. As a YA book about "monsters and the women who like to kiss them" this is clearly her wheelhouse. The setting was colorful and characters unique enough to stand out clearly. The magic of her world was vague, but felt like there was a depth there beyond the hand-wavey. All of that was for the good.\n\nMy issues with the book are mostly about the main character's motivations. When we meet her, we quickly learn that Violeta will do anything, even give up her own life, to protect her brother. She will sacrifice everything she has to protect him, endure physical and emotional trauma, anything. This is who we're cheering for through the entire book when suddenly it all changes.\n\nThis next bit is spoiler-y, so I'm using spoiler tags:\n\nWhen Violeta decides that saving Rowan is worth surrendering the memories of her family for all eternity it just didn't make any sense. It was so entirely against her character that it threw off the rest of the book for me. Once the Lord Under specified that her brother was included in that, and that she'd never remember him, any chance of a better rating went out the window. Honestly at that point of the book it felt like the author forgot that Violeta had a brother at all as she spun up the romance plot, which, in retrospect, was far weaker of a connection to reality than her familial love. No, were I her editor I'd have told her to kill the romance angle completely and have her sacrifice her safety at Lakesedge to save the world, but leave the brother in peace. That fits her character more and avoids the trope.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58306874
5:058419574	6:gr-58419574	3:Lux (Texas Reckoners, #1)	4:book review	60:Lux (Texas Reckoners, #1)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2021	64:Audible Originals	68:read	69:2021-08-23	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58419574
5:000584260	6:gr-584260	3:Masks of Eternity: Power of Myth 6	4:book review	60:Masks of Eternity: Power of Myth 6	61:Joseph Campbell	62:1992	64:HighBridge Audio	68:read	69:2018-07-04	63:9780942110982	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/584260
5:058460032	6:gr-58460032	3:git sync murder	4:book review	60:git sync murder	61:Michael Warren Lucas	62:2021	64:Tilted Windmill Press	68:read	69:2021-07-18	63:9781642350555	67:5/5	70:Dale Whitehead is back at it again. The poor guy deserves a whole Chinese buffet after the crazy events at the tech/sci-fi convention.\n\nBook two brought the familiar sympathies of a tech geek wishing for just a moment for the dream to be real while simultaneously fending off your own endless insecurities. There's plenty of drama in the pages but perhaps the greatest of all is Dale's internal one. Without that earnest interior these books could easily be cliche. Instead they are (sometimes painfully) relatable, entertaining, and thrilling mysteries.\n\nThere's a certain level of tech-geek required to get full enjoyment. If you know what IPv6 is, or how to rebase in git, and you like a good mystery then you're going to love this.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58460032
5:058473038	6:gr-58473038	3:Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: The Last Ronin	4:book review	60:Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles: The Last Ronin	61:Kevin Eastman	62:2022	64:IDW Publishing	68:read	69:2023-03-07	63:9781684058419	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58473038
5:058552575	6:gr-58552575	3:Ink Witch (Kat Dubois Chronicles, #1)	4:book review	60:Ink Witch (Kat Dubois Chronicles, #1)	61:Lindsey Sparks	62:2021	68:read	69:2021-12-30	67:2/5	70:This first book in the Kat Dubois chronicles leaves much to be desired. The characterization of Kat herself is quite inconsistent, with motivations ranging all over from moment to moment. For the amount of time we're told of her raging hormones being trapped in the teenage body we don't really experience it other than one very suspect moment which seemed forced to create a relationship where none existed.\n\nThere are also big gaps in the backstory which clearly reference the Echo trilogy, but without much context. For new readers we have a swath of side characters who all seem vaguely ancient gods, or something.\n\nAs for the plot of the book itself? At any given moment it sure seems like there's a "next step" for the characters to address, but in retrospect none of their motivations make much sense. The goals of individuals change abruptly in a moment. Heck, even the magic in the story seems to change from moment to moment.\n\nThe actual writing is fine and there's some nice scene work here and there. The problems I'm seeing here seem to be a result of a "pantser" that didn't revise enough or have a strong enough editor asking questions.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58552575
5:000586578	6:gr-586578	3:Essential Sufism	4:book review	60:Essential Sufism	61:James Fadiman	62:1999	64:HarperOne	68:read	69:2010-12-26	63:9780062514752	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/586578
5:058673883	6:gr-58673883	3:The Many Deaths of Laila Starr	4:book review	60:The Many Deaths of Laila Starr	61:Ram V.	62:2022	64:BOOM! Studios	68:read	69:2022-02-27	63:9781684158058	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58673883
5:058723521	6:gr-58723521	3:Calling (Sorcery and Society, #3)	4:book review	60:Calling (Sorcery and Society, #3)	61:Molly Harper	62:2022	64:NYLA	68:read	69:2022-04-28	67:2/5	70:Most of the book felt stagnant but there are pockets of action that didn't quite work. The children, used to running amok on their adventures for the last two books, are suddenly chaperoned and yet continue to lead the efforts to address world-scale problems rather than have adults step in. They instead seem to be patiently waiting in the wings for their moment to step in and comment upon the children's work instead.\n\nThe main antagonist devolved into a characature in this story as well. Her previous tretchery as a long-time librarian stealthily working for her own aims is mentioned, but now she's cartoonish instead of subtle. Oh, and the entire plot revolving around the Motherbook is diminished and then basically forgotten despite it's build up in the last two books.\n\nThe actiony ending could have been stronger as well. This author is very good at writing character pieces, dialogue, and introspection, but seemed less practiced at large scale action. There should have been a greater sense of tension, beats that pulled the story forward quickly, and descriptions of the daring action. Instead each build-up of threat was immediately balanced by telling us about the counter plans already in motion. Choatic scenes of fighting are interrupted by dialogue without urgency, and the heroic actions are generically referred to without zooming in.\n\nOverall this was a bit of a disappointment after the strength of the first two books.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58723521
5:000587582	6:gr-587582	3:Queen of Sorcery (The Belgariad #2)	4:book review	60:Queen of Sorcery (The Belgariad #2)	61:David Eddings	62:1982	64:Del Rey	68:read	69:2009-07-03	63:9780345335654	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/587582
5:058764394	6:gr-58764394	3:Backyard Starship (Backyard Starship, #1)	4:book review	60:Backyard Starship (Backyard Starship, #1)	61:J.N. Chaney	62:2021	64:Variant Publications	68:read	69:2022-05-01	67:1/5	70:Really poor reader. Monotone and same voice for all characters. Story is juvenile and cliche	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58764394
5:000058822	6:gr-58822	3:Big Stone Gap (Big Stone Gap, #1)	4:book review	60:Big Stone Gap (Big Stone Gap, #1)	61:Adriana Trigiani	62:2003	64:Fawcett	68:read	69:1998-01-01	63:9780345459206	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58822
5:058960282	6:gr-58960282	3:The Wandering Inn: Book 5 - The Last Light (The Wandering Inn, #4, Part 1)	4:book review	60:The Wandering Inn: Book 5 - The Last Light (The Wandering Inn, #4, Part 1)	61:Pirateaba	62:2021	68:read	69:2021-12-05	67:5/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/58960282
5:005899779	6:gr-5899779	3:Pride and Prejudice and Zombies (Pride and Prejudice and Zombies, #1)	4:book review	60:Pride and Prejudice and Zombies (Pride and Prejudice and Zombies, #1)	61:Seth Grahame-Smith	62:2009	64:Quirk Classics	68:read	69:2014-01-01	63:9781594743344	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5899779
5:059021177	6:gr-59021177	3:Fallout (Expeditionary Force, #13)	4:book review	60:Fallout (Expeditionary Force, #13)	61:Craig Alanson	62:2021	64:Podium Audio	68:read	69:2021-12-17	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59021177
5:000005907	6:gr-5907	3:The Hobbit (The Lord of the Rings, #0)	4:book review	60:The Hobbit (The Lord of the Rings, #0)	61:J.R.R. Tolkien	62:2002	64:Houghton Mifflin	68:read	69:1993-01-01	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5907
5:059247484	6:gr-59247484	3:The Second Storm (A Thousand Li #6)	4:book review	60:The Second Storm (A Thousand Li #6)	61:Tao Wong	62:2021	64:Starlit Publishing	68:read	69:2022-07-10	63:1990491340	67:4/5	70:This may be my favorite book so far. There are times when it's a little tricky keeping all the characters straight especially as I'm not well practiced at east asian names, but the vibrant characters themselves helped. Cultivation novels are really growing on me.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59247484
5:059344312	6:gr-59344312	3:Verity	4:book review	60:Verity	61:Colleen Hoover	62:2021	64:Grand Central Publishing	68:read	69:2022-08-22	63:9781538724743	67:4/5	70:That was pretty messed up. :)\n\nThis is a departure from my usual genre fiction, but was recommended by someone with excellent taste. The amount of sexual focus threw me off at first and I wasn't sure if it was something coming from the romance background or not, but by the end of the story it was fully justified. Given such a small setting and the few characters it had a remarkable amount of tension and thrill. I didn't expect the ending either!	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59344312
5:059515764	6:gr-59515764	3:Dreadgod (Cradle, #11)	4:book review	60:Dreadgod (Cradle, #11)	61:Will Wight	62:2022	64:Hidden Gnome Publishing	68:read	69:2022-08-20	67:5/5	70:Well that took an unexpected turn! Still the best cultivation series around.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59515764
5:059604880	6:gr-59604880	3:The Kaiju Preservation Society	4:book review	60:The Kaiju Preservation Society	61:John Scalzi	62:2022	64:Audible Studios	68:read	69:2022-03-22	67:4/5	70:As Scalzi says, this is a pop song of a novel. It's three minutes of light hearted joy. There's bad guys and monsters and cool action and science, but its mostly just a joyful and silly read.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59604880
5:059796919	6:gr-59796919	3:Ghost Hunters Adventure Club and the Express Train to Nowhere (2)	4:book review	60:Ghost Hunters Adventure Club and the Express Train to Nowhere (2)	61:Cecil H.H. Mills	62:2022	64:Permuted Press	68:read	69:2023-08-13	63:9781637581841	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/59796919
