5:006599342	6:gr-6599342	3:The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (Millennium, #1)	4:book review	60:The Girl with the Dragon Tattoo (Millennium, #1)	61:Stieg Larsson	62:2008	64:Vintage	68:read	69:2012-11-06	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6599342
5:006604209	6:gr-6604209	3:Mistborn Trilogy Boxed Set (Mistborn, #1-3)	4:book review	60:Mistborn Trilogy Boxed Set (Mistborn, #1-3)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2009	64:Tor Fantasy	68:read	69:2012-01-01	63:9780765365439	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6604209
5:000664442	6:gr-664442	3:The First Jesuits	4:book review	60:The First Jesuits	61:John W. O'Malley	62:1995	64:Harvard University Press	68:read	69:2011-03-09	63:9780674303133	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/664442
5:000664444	6:gr-664444	3:Contemplatives in Action: The Jesuit Way	4:book review	60:Contemplatives in Action: The Jesuit Way	61:William A. Barry	62:2002	64:Paulist Press	68:read	69:2009-08-20	63:9780809141128	67:4/5	70:In this short volume, William Barry attempts to show the many creative tensions that work in the heart of Jesuits today and through history. With roots in the founding of the society, this work expounds on the changes that have shaped and shaken the society and the hearts of individuals among its numbers and those whose development for which it has been responsible. In all things, Barry attempts to provide a fair assessment, acknowledging not only the many graces of the Jesuits, but also the many times the society has strayed from its core values, whether those be internally in its structural and hierarchical relationships, its relationship to the world, or even its relationship to God. \n\nThe book is a wonderfully written overview of what it means to be a Jesuit, and should be near the top of the reading lists for those people discerning a call to religious life within the society, or those who find their lives surrounded by those interesting individuals.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/664444
5:000006656	6:gr-6656	3:The Divine Comedy	4:book review	60:The Divine Comedy	61:Dante Alighieri	62:1995	64:Everyman's Library	68:read	69:1996-01-01	63:9780679433132	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6656
5:006665847	6:gr-6665847	3:Daemon (Daemon, #1)	4:book review	60:Daemon (Daemon, #1)	61:Daniel Suarez	62:2009	64:Signet Books	68:read	69:2021-03-24	63:9780451228734	67:2/5	70:When I started this story I was impressed that the author was taking care to describe technology accurately. For instance, when a character needs to hack into a wifi connection the process he uses is spot on for that type of encryption. It was sadly hamstrung in the audiobook by a reader who seemed much less familiar with the tech than the author. Stunted narration and odd pronunciations really made things seem awkward.\n\nPretty quickly the story was filled with action and violence. The characters were diverse and interesting and it was a bit of a mystery where things would turn.\n\nAnd so it was pretty sad when the end let me down. Characters didn't fulfill their potential, and sometimes seemed to forget their own motivations. The big message wasn't really there, nor was there a sense of resolution. The book was holding a pretty strong 3.5 rating until that point. Oh well.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/6665847
5:000666758	6:gr-666758	3:The Knowledge of the Holy	4:book review	60:The Knowledge of the Holy	61:A.W. Tozer	62:1978	64:HarperOne	68:read	69:2020-01-16	63:9780060684129	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/666758
