5:000717726	6:gr-717726	3:Italian Stories: A Dual-Language Book (Dover Dual Language Italian)	4:book review	60:Italian Stories: A Dual-Language Book (Dover Dual Language Italian)	61:Robert A. Hall Jr.	62:1990	64:Dover Publications	68:read	69:2001-01-01	63:9780486261805	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/717726
5:000719180	6:gr-719180	3:20,000 Leagues Under the Sea	4:book review	60:20,000 Leagues Under the Sea	61:Jules Verne	62:2003	64:Scholastic Paperbacks	68:read	69:1994-01-01	63:9780439227155	67:3/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/719180
5:007202841	6:gr-7202841	3:Locke & Key, Vol. 3: Crown of Shadows	4:book review	60:Locke & Key, Vol. 3: Crown of Shadows	61:Joe Hill	62:2013	64:IDW Publishing	68:read	69:2021-05-22	63:9781600106958	67:4/5	70:This one flowed better than the last. I like where this is going.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7202841
5:007235533	6:gr-7235533	3:The Way of Kings (The Stormlight Archive, #1)	4:book review	60:The Way of Kings (The Stormlight Archive, #1)	61:Brandon Sanderson	62:2010	64:Tor Books	68:read	69:2011-10-19	63:9780765326355	67:5/5	70:I absolutely loved this book. I can't wait for the next in the series.\n\nI bought it in hardback instead of on my kindle because I'd heard there were lots of maps in the print that were unreadable in the digital versions. Well, I think that sentiment is completely right, but it's more than maps. Character journals, sketches, and all sorts of things are spread in the pages. It's great to flip back to the awesome maps in the beginning too. It's certainly possible to enjoy the book without all the pictures, or to look them up online for reference. The book is really big and cumbersome too, so there's that to worry about. I guess if the worst thing you have to worry about with this book is what version to buy, that says something in itself.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7235533
5:000724371	6:gr-724371	3:The Lady of Shalott	4:book review	60:The Lady of Shalott	61:Alfred Tennyson	62:1999	64:Oxford University Press	68:read	69:2011-01-01	63:9780192723710	67:4/5	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/724371
5:007260188	6:gr-7260188	3:Mockingjay (The Hunger Games, #3)	4:book review	60:Mockingjay (The Hunger Games, #3)	61:Suzanne Collins	62:2010	64:Scholastic Press	68:read	69:2012-01-03	63:9780439023511	67:3/5	70:This book had a lot of neat stuff going for it, but the ending let me down. There's not a lot of rules I hold sacred in writing. "Your character should be the instigator of change," is one of them. Katniss Everdeen was not that instrument of change.\n\nIn book 1, she was the actor, the catalyst, that drove the story. Her actions changed the plot and drove it to its epic conclusion.\n\nIn book 2, her confusion set in, and while she made a lot of decisions, it was the people around her who really drove the action. Sure, a few key moments were hers, but she was reactive, not active.\n\nIn book 3, Katniss really didn't do much except wander around acting as a symbol and being grumpy, confused, or broken. The epic conclusion would have played out pretty much the same had she not existed. Some small things would have changed, sure, but they were mostly things dealing with the big (and pointless) twist at the end. \n\nI have no issue with the deaths of specific characters, or the choices of who ended up with whom, but I can't forgive being stuck in a useless character for the whole book. This one should have been written from Gale's POV.	71:https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7260188
